<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Troops in Gulf Refuse Anthrax Jab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Defense Sunday
refused to rule out the compulsory vaccination of British troops
going to areas such as Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, BBC TV reported nearly three-quarters of British
servicemen deployed to the Middle East during February's Gulf
crisis refused anti-anthrax injections because of fears over Gulf
war syndrome.
</P>
<P>
The anthrax jab is the same as one that formed part of a
cocktail of injections blamed by some for outbreaks of mysterious
illness among veterans of the 1991 Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
George Robertson, the defense secretary, was publicly
vaccinated in an attempt to rebuild confidence in the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
However, on Britain's Gulf flagship, the aircraft carrier
Invincible, not a single sailor in the 1,200-strong crew took the
injection.
</P>
<P>
On Illustrious, the carrier that replaced Invincible, only two
sailors agreed to be vaccinated. The low take-up of the jabs was
regarded here as a blow to the secretary.
</P>
<P>
Every serviceman was reported to receive a letter from
Robertson assuring them that the vaccine was safe and that their
protection was "paramount."
</P>
<P>
But officials from the Ministry of Defense believe that troops
concern about Gulf war syndrome outweighed fear of being attacked.
</P>
<P>
One official was quoted as saying, "If we force people to take
the vaccine, we will be accused of compromising their rights, and
if we don't, we will be accused of ignoring their safety."
</P>
</TEXT>
