<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Rejects UN Security Council Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 7 (Xinhua) -- India Sunday evening rejected the
U.N. Security Council resolution issued Saturday urging India and
Pakistan to halt their further nuclear weapons program.
</P>
<P>
India's senior External Affairs Ministry officials regarded the
resolution as "ultra virus" and "unacceptable". Following up New
Delhi's strong reaction to the resolution, the officials said that
exception had been taken to the "deeply offensive" tone and the
manner in which it had addressed India.
</P>
<P>
They termed the resolution as "coercive" and "unhelpful". They
said that "contending the problem of non-proliferation could not
be arbitrarily confined to a narrow geographical segment, but
addressed meaningfully only in a global framework."
</P>
<P>
The officials argued, "India did not recognize the council's
role in trying to address the issue of non-proliferation which was
not provided in its charter."
</P>
<P>
"We find it strange that attempts have been made to coerce
member states to accede to international treaties. This is
contrary to the norms of international law," they said.
</P>
<P>
The council's move had not contributed in any manner to
international peace and stability, they further said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, these officials also assailed the council for
its reference to the Kashmir issue in the resolution, describing
it as "unwarranted" and "unnecessary". They said, "India was
awaiting a formal response from Pakistan to its renewed offer for
a direct comprehensive dialogue with Islamabad to address all
outstanding issues, including Kashmir." They made it clear,
however, that "it would not accept any third party mediation" over
the Kashmir issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
