<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Denies Report on Ties With France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Foreign
Affairs Department Sunday denied a newspaper report that Pretoria
is trying to avoid being too close to France when French
President Jacques Chirac visits the country at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
Sunday Times quoted South African officials as saying,
"South Africa is wary of being associated too closely with France
in Africa, although Pretoria is happy to deal with Paris on
issues of trade, culture and technology."
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Affairs Department said in a statement that it had
noted the article with concern.
</P>
<P>
"The department would like to point out that this article is
speculative and contains inaccuracies. It does not reflect the
true nature of the state of bilateral relations between South
Africa and France."
</P>
<P>
South Africa highly values its strategic partnership with
France and political and economic relations are on an excellent
footing, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The article, entitled "SA (South Africa) won't let Chirac use
Mandela on Visit," said the planned state visit has caused
anxious behind-scenes by both countries.
</P>
<P>
It quoted South African foreign affairs officials as saying
that France, using the high-profile visit by U.S. President Bill
Clinton in March as a precedent, had insisted Mandela accompany
Chirac on at least five occasions.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has made it clear that Mandela will host a
face-to-face meeting with the French president and a state
banquet -- normal protocol for a head of state, the article said.
</P>
<P>
However, according to the article, France asked for Mandela to
accompany Chirac to a France-South Africa business conference in
Johannesburg and on visits to Soweto, a black township near
Johannesburg, and Robben Island off Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Affairs Department said the program for the visit,
scheduled for June 26-28, was still being finalized, and
therefore speculation about specific program items was premature
at this stage.
</P>
<P>
The paper said France regarded the visit as key to the
promotion of its revamped African policy, which is aimed at
broadening French interests outside French-speaking countries and
which France hopes will have a special focus on southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted South African officials as saying that they
were concerned France wished to use the perception of a
friendship between Mandela and Chirac as a way of promoting the
new French policy.
</P>
<P>
"We are sensitive about the perception of a joint French-South
African onslaught on Africa -- that the two countries are
`colonizing` Africa," one official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The paper also quoted a scholar, Deon Fourie, as saying that
"Chirac wants France to play a role in Africa in line with
conservative thinking. South Africa sees French interests as
neo-colonial and would not want to aid that."
</P>
<P>
Chirac would also visit Namibia, Mozambique and Angola.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
