<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Refugee Situation in Africa Still Serious </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African
Unity (OAU) has asked its member states to address the root
causes of the refugees and to create the propitious conditions to
spare their populations forced movements and asylum drive.
</P>
<P>
The countries of origin should promote peace, security and
stability so as to encourage voluntary repatriation of refugees
and return of displaced persons to their usual places of
residence, said a resolution adopted by the 68th ordinary session
of OAU council of ministers which comes to an end Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
The basic principles enshrined in the U.N. and OAU conventions
on refugees should be respected, said the resolution.
</P>
<P>
The session expressed its gratitude to the member states which
have offered asylum and assistance to refugees in the spirit of
African solidarity and brotherhood.
</P>
<P>
It also expressed thanks to the international community and
humanitarian organizations giving assistance to refugees and
displaced persons, particularly, UNHCR and ICRC and urged them to
increase their assistance in order to alleviate the suffering of
the refugees and displaced persons in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Available statistics show that in spite of some positive
developments which have led to some repartiation exercises in
some member states, a lot still remains to be done by all parties
concerned to address this dehumanizing problem of refugees and
displaced persons as the refugee population still stands to about
6 million and that of displaced persons is estimated close to 20
million, and in both categories, a majority of the victims are
women and children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
