<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Restricts Number of Eritrean Diplomats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia announced Sunday that
it has ordered the Eritrean Embassy to Ethiopia to limit the
number of its diplomatic staff to three and the rest to leave
Ethiopia at noon on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the Ethiopian Foreign Ministry said
the measures were taken following "the uncivilized act by the
authorities in Asmara."
</P>
<P>
Eritrea's air raid against the city of Mekelle in north
Ethiopia last week which claimed the lives of 44 people and
wounded 135 others was a premeditated strike that aimed at
unleashing terror among the civilian population, the press
release said.
</P>
<P>
It said the bombs were dropped twice, the first on a school
and the second on a crowd assisting victims.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean authorities have provoked the hostilities when
"they occupied Ethiopian territory and rejected a recommendation
proposed by the facilitators who have attempted to defuse the
tension triggered by Eritrean aggression," the press release
added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Ethiopian News Agency reported that 48 of the
Eritrean diplomatic staff in Ethiopia have left the country at
noon Sunday in accordance with the order given by the Ethiopian
government.
</P>
<P>
The only remaining staff are the Eritrean ambassador and his
two aides, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The border dispute between the two Horn of African countries
turned violent when either side accused the other of invasion.
</P>
<P>
The row centers on a rocky 400 square km triangle of land
which both countries claim. 
</P>
</TEXT>
