<HEADLINE> Yeltsin, Blair Discuss Nuke Tests, Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin had
a telephone conversation Sunday evening with Britain Prime
Minister Tony Blair and the two discussed "virtually all urgent
international issues," the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The topics covered in the lengthy discussion included nuclear
tests by India and Pakistan, the conflict in Kosovo, Yugoslavia,
and the upcoming meeting in London of the foreign ministers of the
Group of Eight countries.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders called for coordinated actions by major powers
toward keeping intact the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty and the
prevention of the spread of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
They welcomed the outcome of the Geneva meeting on the issue
Thursday of the foreign ministers of the five permanent member
countries of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The two urged a speedy solution to the Kosovo conflict and
Blair expressed the hope that any settlement should include
maintenance of Yugoslavia's territorial integrity, Interfax
reported, quoting the presidential press service.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and Blair also discussed bilateral cooperation and
agreed to continue regular contacts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
