<HEADLINE> Egypt Calls for World Treaty on Nuclear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
Sunday called for the creation of an international disarmament
treaty to rid the world of nuclear weapons within two decades.
</P>
<P>
"I have been wishing that all weapons of mass destruction be
eliminated from the whole world and that an international treaty
be reached covering 15 or 17 years after which the world would get
rid of weapons of mass destruction," Mubarak said after casting
his vote in the mid-term election of Shura Council, the Egyptian
parliament's consultative body.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, who has campaigned for a nuclear-free Middle East
since early 1990s, expressed concern that the recent Indian and
Pakistani nuclear tests might encourage other countries in the
region to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
"Israel, as well as India and Pakistan, possesses nuclear
weapons and it is possible that other countries would carry out
their nuclear tests, like Iran and others," he was quoted by
Egypt's Middle East News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The president said these states will encourage other
non-nuclear countries to enter this field out of fear that they
would be exposed, even by mistake, to the threats of such weapons.
</P>
<P>
On the Egyptian stance in this respect, the president said: "We
call for eliminating all weapons of mass destruction not only
from the Middle East but from the whole world through an
international treaty as these weapons threaten all mankind."
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been urging Israel, which is believed to be the only
nuclear power in the Middle East, to sign the Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty and open its arsenal to international
inspection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
