<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Plans to Double Number of High-Tech Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- To meet the need of its rapidly
expanding high-tech sector, Israeli government began discussing a
plan Sunday aimed at drastically increasing the number of
university graduates in high-tech fields.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Education Minister Yitzhak
Levy and Labor and Social Affairs Minister Eli Yishai discussed
with university heads ways how to double the number of high-tech
workers from 30,000 to 60,000 within five years.
</P>
<P>
Of the 30,000 new workers, about two-thirds would be university
and college graduates in the fields of electronics and computers,
while the remaining third would be graduates in non-technology
fields, who would undergo retraining. This category would include
new immigrants.
</P>
<P>
The plan, submitted by the Council for Higher Education, was
designed to sustain the rapid growth of Israel's high-tech
sectors. There are currently about 3,500 high-tech companies in
Israel, and the high-tech products account for 80 percent of
Israel's total exports.
</P>
<P>
A shortage of high-tech personnel has developed in recent
years, and Israeli companies have even turned to other countries
for recruiting computer programmers and electronics engineers.
</P>
<P>
Professor Nehemia Levtzion, head of the council's Planning and
Budget Committee, said Saturday that the number of graduates from
academic institutions in high-tech areas would increase from about
2,000 to 4,000 annually by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
He expressed satisfaction that, for the first time, Israel's
government, academia and industry are ready to ensure the
continued growth of high-technology industries by making available
trained personnel in the quantity and quality needed by the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu asked the council two months ago to devise a plan to
increase the number of university and college students in the
high-tech fields in order to preserve Israel's relative advantage
in high-tech industries and to enable increased exports.
</P>
<P>
Levtzion said that the high-tech industry would continue to
expand for as long as it continues to offer computer science and
electronics engineering graduates professional challenges and
good working conditions.
</P>
<P>
The professor added that the current plan to increase the
number of high-tech students was supported by the Finance
Ministry, which will increase the annual budget of the
participating institutions accordingly despite the budgetary
cuts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
