<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Takes Common Position on Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The grave child labor
situation in Africa has aroused much concern among ministers
attending the 68th ordinary session of the council of ministers
of the Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
In a resolution adopted by the session which is to end Sunday
night, all delegates agreed on the African Common Position and
plan of action on child labor in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The resolution endorses the report of the OAU
Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim as well as the
recommendations put forward by the 21st session of the OAU Labor
and Social Affairs Commission held in Pretoria, South Africa,
from 13 to 18, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The recommendations will constitute the African common
position on child labor.
</P>
<P>
The recommendations suggest that OAU member states urgently
sign, ratify and implement the African Charter on the Rights and
Welfare of the Child in order to ensure the protection, welfare
and development of the African children.
</P>
<P>
The 68th session asked the OAU secretary-general in
collaboration with United Nations Children's Fund, International
Labor Organization (ILO) and social partners to carry out a study
and devise an appropriate strategy, persuade member states to
sign and ratify the charter to ensure its coming into force as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
According to the most recent ILO data, there are about 80
million child workers in Africa, the highest number than in any
other part of the world. Against this background, the future is
gloomy and if the current economic and social trends persist, the
number of child laborers in Africa could swell to well over 100
million by the year 2015.
</P>
<P>
Child labor, as defined by OAU, is work, paid or unpaid, which
deprives the child of an education or threatens safety, health,
or morals which is considered as exploitation of the child, even
when employed in family enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In order to find solutions to the most intolerable, hazardous
and abusive forms of child labor, a number of international
meetings have been held in recent years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
