<HEADLINE> Blair Discusses Kosovo With US, Russia Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 7 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
discussed the crisis in Kosovo in phone calls to U.S. President
Bill Clinton and Russian President Boris Yeltsin, BBC TV reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Blair agreed with Clinton to send a strong message criticizing
the acts of Yugoslav forces in the province, it added.
</P>
<P>
While talking with Yeltsin, the premier urged him to help
persuade Belgrade to stop "barbarism" against Albanian civilians
in Kosovo, BBC TV said.
</P>
<P>
It was also reported widely that Blair has ordered 1,000 troops
to go on standby to stop the situation in Kosovo turning into a
bloodbath.
</P>
<P>
The Observer quoted a British source as saying, "The page has
been turned, we have entered a detailed period of military
planning."
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Mail said Blair has won crucial support for the plan
from Clinton. In a classified diplomatic message from Washington,
Clinton said he would contribute 1,500 soldiers and help to
enforce a no-fly zone over Kosovo, the paper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
