<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Slams Iraqi Statement on Border Demarcation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait on Sunday flatly
rejected the Iraqi statement that shed doubt on U.N. Security
Council Resolution 833 on the demarcation of the Kuwait-Iraq
borders.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan was reported to have
said in Rabat, Morocco, that there was no legal value in the
Resolution 833 concerning the demarcation of the borders between
Kuwait and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Kuwaiti Cabinet after its weekly
session said that the Iraqi stance was a "serious threat" and
revealed the true Iraqi intentions against the State of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet said the Kuwait-Iraq border demarcation was based
on the agreements existing between the two states as well as
documents and testimonials submitted by the sides.
</P>
<P>
It added that the demarcation was done through the precise
technical work by the U.N. committee entrusted with border
setting, and that the process was not just a reallocation of
territories.
</P>
<P>
This demarcation was legalized by the U.N. Security Council in
a unanimous vote, by the border demarcation committee resolutions
and the endorsement by the Iraqi government itself, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Kuwaiti Foreign Ministry Friday deplored the
Iraqi statement, saying that Kuwait would take legal and
political actions required at both Arab and international arenas
to preserve the country's rights and enforce the full
implementation of relevant Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait led to the Gulf War in 1991,
which ended with Iraq's defeat. In May 1993, the U.N. Security
Council adopted the Resolution 833 on the demarcation of
Iraqi-Kuwait borders based on the recommendations put forward by a
U.N. demarcation committee.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait approved the resolution shortly after its passage, but
Iraq only accepted it in November 1994 as part of its efforts to
end the U.N. sanctions imposed after the Gulf War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
