<HEADLINE> Iraq, Jordan Start Talks on Health Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi and Jordanian officials
Sunday held talks on promoting bilateral cooperation in health
area in an effort to help the worsening health situation in the
sanctions-ridden Iraq.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, officials from the two sides discussed means
of developing bilateral relations in health area and stressed the
importance of exchanging visits and medical and pharmaceutical
expertise, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Health Minister Omed Medhat Mubarak reviewed the
deteriorating health situation and the impact of continuing U.N.
sanctions on Iraq, saying hundreds of thousands of Iraqi people,
mostly children, have died as a result of sanctions-caused
shortage of food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions were imposed on Iraq in 1990 after its
invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Ashraf Kurdi, the Jordanian health minister, who
arrived here on Friday leading a medical delegation, hailed Iraq's
national position and its people's steadfastness and courage in
facing up to the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that his ministry's service was placed at the
disposal of the Iraqi health and medical institutions.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed that three special committees would be set
up to consider curative, preventive and medical matters.
</P>
<P>
A Jordanian medical team participating in the current
Iraqi-Jordanian medical week on Sunday performed a number of
surgeries in Iraqi hospitals of eye diseases, digestive apparatus,
bone fracture and heart diseases.
</P>
<P>
Kurdi has said his visit to Iraq and the Iraqi-Jordanian
medical week were the beginning of a broader and more
comprehensive cooperation with Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
