<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Visits Sudan to Continue Push for Arab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
visited Sudan Sunday in his continued bid to push for holding an
Arab summit to pressure Israel to carry out the long-delayed
further redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Arafat concluded his several-hour visit following talks with
President Omar al-Bashir on the Middle East peace process and
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
But top on his agenda here was to solicit Sudanese support for
his idea of holding an Arab summit to discuss the protracted
deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival here, Arafat blasted Israel for pushing the
region into the current state of tension and crisis by failing to
abide sincerely and accurately by the signed Israeli-Palestinian
accords.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader stressed that the peace accords with
Israel are not bilateral but international ones signed by Russia,
the U.S., the European Union, Norway, Egypt and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
He once again urged the international community to take
actions to save the signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's Sudanese visit was apparently part of his ongoing
efforts to convene an Arab summit in order to formulate a common
Arab strategy to confront the Israeli intransigence. The
Israeli-Palestinian talks have been stalled for over one year
mainly because of Israel's repeated delays in carrying out further
troop redeployments in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Since late May, Arafat has already visited Egypt, Saudi Arabia,
United Arab Emirates, Oman, Jordan and Yemen to lobby for support
for holding an Arab summit. Although most Arab leaders have agreed
to attend such summit, no agreement has been reached on when,
where and how to hold it due to the difference over what stance
should take toward Israel.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said the call for holding an Arab summit aims not only
to review the Middle East peace process, but also to discuss ways
of restoring unity and solidarity among the Arab world. It will
also explore ways of facing up to the challenges posed to the Arab
world as one integrated and cohesive power at this delicate stage,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made clear that the time and venue of the summit have
not been specified so far and that most of the Arab countries
which he has contacted agreed on holding the summit.
</P>
<P>
"Since the Madrid Peace Conference, the Arab nation was keen on
the Middle East peace process under the land-for-peace banner,
while Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu raises the
security-for-peace banner," Arafat said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
