<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Vows to Boost Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- African ministers Sunday
reaffirmed their determination to boost education for the
development of the continent's immense natural riches and
numerous potentials.
</P>
<P>
At the end of its 68th ordinary session, the council of the
ministers of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) agreed to
adopt the strategy on the establishment of the coordination,
follow-up and evaluation mechanisms to facilitate the
implementation of the first decade of education in Africa between
1997 and 2006.
</P>
<P>
The council also adopted a draft program of action of the
decade of education, which was launched by OAU in November 1997
as a collective effort to promote education in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The program of action aims to help translate into concrete
terms the political will of African countries to establish
education systems suitable to the development of the continent.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, African countries should endeavor to give
access to basic education for all Africans, develop technical and
vocational education, beef up higher education and research, as
well as language education to facilitate exchanges among African
countries, where a good number of languages are used.
</P>
<P>
The priority areas of the program also cover education for
girls and women, and children in all conditions.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the training of teachers, the comprehensive
program also stresses education of adults in rural areas, working
adults, the unemployed and refugees in a broad field ranging from
civic education to that for regional integration and
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
According to OAU Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim,
diminishing financial resources and the growing demand for
education and training have constituted the major challenges that
Africa has to face up to at the dawn of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The program therefore proposed that African countries build a
purposeful will to help release resources and pool resources by
all possible means.
</P>
<P>
The mechanisms for coordination, follow-up and evaluation
institution should be established for various countries to steer
the implementation of the program to the objectives at regional
and continental levels.
</P>
<P>
Thus the council of ministers requested all OAU member states
and sub-regional economic communities to cooperate with OAU by
drawing up their respective programs of action and establishing
similar structures for harmonized conduct of activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
