<HEADLINE> Hussein Optimistic About Resuming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Following talks with Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai here Sunday, Jordan's King Hussein said
that he is optimistic about resuming the long-stalled
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Hussein said this was because Israel is considering the peace
proposal put forward by the United States and ready to sign an
agreement with the Palestinians on troops withdrawal from the
occupied West Bank.
</P>
<P>
During his whirlwind visit here, Mordechai briefed Hussein on
the Israeli government's latest ideas about the U.S. proposal
aimed at restoring the deadlocked peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"I'm more optimistic," said Hussein to reporters after the
meeting. "I'm satisfied with what I heard from Mordechai and I
hope that things will move in the right direction."
</P>
<P>
As to the U.S. peace proposal, the king said that it is an
important one which came as the result of long study and should
deserve positive response. He added that he was glad to see that
the U.S. remains to be the main sponsor of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Mordechai said that Israel is still considering
the U.S. proposal calling for a 13 percent Israeli withdrawal in
the second stage of three-phase pullbacks in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Under the framework of the U.S. proposal, the Israeli
government will "soon" reach an agreement with the Palestinians
on the Israeli troop withdrawal and both sides will "find a way to
move forward with the peace process," said Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
"There are some projects and some ideas that need to be
encouraged by everyone -- in the Israeli side, in the Palestinian
side -- and of course by His Majesty the king, to support the
peace process," added the minister, while declining to give more
details.
</P>
<P>
This was the second official visit that Mordechai paid to Arab
countries in the past weeks to promote the Israeli idea about the
U.S. proposal. He went to Egypt to meet President Hosni Mubarak
last week.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been trying to prevent the holding of an proposed
Arab summit being actively pushed by Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat, who hopes to exert pressure on Israel over the
redeployment issue.
</P>
<P>
In recent days, hopes emerged that an agreement on the
redeployment is imminent because Israel is closer to accepting the
U.S. pullback plan.
</P>
<P>
But the optimism has been dampened Sunday by remarks made by
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu who told the weekly
Cabinet meeting that "it is not possible we are on the verge of an
agreement." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
