<HEADLINE> Sudan Renews Support for Arab Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar al-Bashir
renewed Sunday his country's support for holding a summit grouping
all the Arab countries to discuss problems facing the Arab nation,
including the Mideast peace.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with visiting Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat here, al-Bashir told reporters that
the Arab nation is in need of reviewing the situation in the Arab
arena to adopt a position that guarantees the restoration of the
Arab rights, safety and security.
</P>
<P>
He voiced hope that the proposed summit would be a step forward
to the restoration of the Arab solidarity and unification of the
Arab rank, pointing out that without unity, the Arabs would never
be able to foil the conspiracies targeting them.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the summit would normalize relations
among the Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Arafat said that his call for an Arab summit does
not aim to deal with the stalemate of the Middle East peace
process only, but it also seek to restore the Arab solidarity and
joint action, thus enabling the Arab nation to face up to the
challenges as one integrated power.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference after his meeting with al-Bashir,
Arafat said that contacts are still underway and that some of the
Arab leaders who have been contacted are against the summit.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived here from Cairo for a several-hour visit before
heading for the summit of Organization of African Unity, due to
open on Monday in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso. 
</P>
