<HEADLINE> Egyptian, Israeli Peace Activists Joinly Bash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- In an unprecedented development, two
Egyptian and Israeli peace movements joined hands in a grass-roots
campaign seeking the change of the policies of Israel's Likud
government towards the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
A joint document will come to light after a full year of
serious discussions and studies by popular forces and
intellectuals to face the serious deterioration of the process,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency quoted Egyptian peace activist
Lotfi el Khouli as saying on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The document pronounces an outright rejection to the policies
of the Likud government, said Khouli, member of the Egyptian Peace
Movement, a group that features a number of prominent writers and
intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
The document will be made public at a joint press conference
given by the Egyptian Peace Movement and Israel's Peace Now
movement in Cairo on Monday, he said.
</P>
<P>
A delegation of Peace Now, Israel's largest peace group with
thousand of members, arrived here on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Khouli said the document provides a further step towards the
Copenhagen Peace Declaration, which was launched in January 1997
through an initiative by European intellectuals and called for
cooperation among world peace activists.
</P>
<P>
"It is the first time intellectuals and popular forces
contribute in a public and organized manner to abort the policies
of Netanyahu and the radical forces and open the door to a just,
balanced and overall peace," he added.
</P>
<P>
The main purpose of this unparalleled document is to "guide
peace on the popular, intellectual and cultural levels to override
the stalemate," he said, adding that "our main affliction is to
change the policies and not the government."
</P>
<P>
The Mideast peace process has been gradually grounded to a
standstill since the Likud government taking power two years
ago. International mediation has so far failed to change the
Israeli hard-line policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Denies IMF Pressure Behind Bank Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Minister of Economy Yousef
Boutros Ghali Sunday categorically denied that Egypt has bowed to
pressure by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) in privatizing
its state-owned banks.
</P>
<P>
In a television interview here, Ghali said the agreement that
Egypt signed in 1991 with the IMF will end in July and there will
be no other agreements in future, an indication that Egypt no
longer needs to borrow money as its economy is going strong.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that Egypt "might seek some foreign
experience to develop the banking sector. But Egyptians will be
responsible in the first place for the developing of this
important sector."
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported Sunday that the Egyptian Trade Union Federation (ETUF)
will set up a special committee to discuss the protection of the
rights of bank workers and improving banking services during the
privatization process.
</P>
<P>
ETUF Secretary General Mohamed Moursi said shares should be
offered first to bank employees, then to Egyptian investors and
finally to Arab investors.
</P>
<P>
"The sale of shares should be in accordance with fixed
percentages and the role of the state should continue to provide
guarantees to depositors, in order to protect them against any
economic shakes and to encourage citizens to invest their money in
national banks so that they may continue to play their economic
role," he added.
</P>
<P>
ETUF does not oppose privatizing the banks so long as the
rights and benefits of workers are protected, Moursi said.
</P>
<P>
A parliamentary sub-committee on the economy approved in May a
bill to privatize the four national banks, namely the National
Bank of Egypt, Misr Bank, Bank of Alexandria and Bank du
Caire. The four banks hold 70 percent of the country's commercial
assets, 60 percent of deposits and 68 percent of loans.
</P>
<P>
The parliament is expected to vote for privatization in
mid-June, allowing the government to put the banks on sale before
the end of the year, although actual privatization would begin later.
</P>
<P>
The move to privatize the banks and state-held insurance
companies has unleashed a wave of protests in Egypt, as opponents
warned that the sale of national banks would undermine the economy.
</P>
<P>
But Ghali has assured earlier that the privatization process
would be accompanied by strict government measures to protect
depositors, including Central Bank intervention in case of
problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
