<HEADLINE> Cyprus: U.S. Embassy Letter Not A Sign of War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government has
clarified that a letter issued by the U.S. Embassy here to its
citizens in Cyprus is not a sign that the embassy fears a war on
the island over the Russian missiles.
</P>
<P>
A written statement by government spokesman Christos
Stylianides available Sunday said "it has been clarified after an
investigation, and assurances have been given by the U.S. Embassy
that the letter is normal practice in order to fill in the
personal data of the list of American citizens living in Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Stylianides was responding to a TV report on Friday night that
the U.S. Embassy had issued a letter to its citizens living in
Cyprus, requesting information on the number of Americans living
on the island.
</P>
<P>
The TV report has suggested that the letters were sent because
of U.S. fears over the planned deployment of the Russian S-300
missiles on the island later in the year.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides said that the U.S. Embassy has also assured the
Cypriot government that the process is carried out at regular
intervals.
</P>
<P>
The embassy, however, said earlier in the week that it did have
a contingency plan for the evacuation of the 2,000 or so
U.S. citizens on the island.
</P>
<P>
A similar report in the British press a week ago caused
outrage on the island when it was revealed that the British
government had a contingency plan to evacuate 250,000 British
tourists in the event of war.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus openly accused Britain's Defense Ministry of leaking
the information in an effort to prevent the deployment of the
missiles. As a result, Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides Friday
snubbed the Queen's official birthday celebrations on the British
bases in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government ordered the Russian-made surface-to-air
S-300 missile system in January 1997, which is expected to be
deployed on the island in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
The deal was criticized by the U.S., Britain and some others,
and met strong opposition from Turkey, which has threatened to
destroy the missiles if they are deployed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
