<HEADLINE> Philippine President Unhappy With Pilots' Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos on Monday
condemned as "unpatriotic" the strike by some pilots of Philippine
Airlines (PAL), saying they were abandoning their planes and
passengers in Bangkok and Hong Kong who were on their way to
Manila.
</P>
<P>
Ramos expressed his dismay during a briefing for
President-Elect and Vice President Joseph Estrada and members of
his new cabinet Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Ramos cited the plight of passengers who were stranded in
Bangkok over the weekend when the PAL pilots declared a strike,
according to the Philippine News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said the act was "unpatriotic" since the pilot could have
flown the plane to Manila as it was home bound.
</P>
<P>
The PAL management has fired all leaders and members of its
620-strong pilots union for declaring a strike which entered the
third day Monday.
</P>
<P>
Talks are still going on to resolve the strike which has
crippled PAL's domestic and international operations.
</P>
<P>
PAL, the country's flag carrier, is losing some 150 million
pesos a day as a result of the work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
The pilots have been staging the strike in protest of a new
policy of the PAL management to retire pilots who have logged
20,000 flying hours. The pilots condemned the action as unfair and
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
But the PAL management said the policy was already contained in
a collective bargaining agreement signed by the union and the PAL
earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
