<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Urges All States to Work Towards Drug-Free World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Monday called on all states to coordinate their efforts and
work towards a drug-free world.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the Special Session of the
General Assembly on the World Drug Problem, Annan expressed the
hope that this session will be the time when the international
community found common ground in the mission to create momentum
towards a drug-free world in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
"The proposed Political Declaration is the product of hard work
and effort. It is rare for consensus to be reached on substantive
as well as political issues months in advance of a Special
Session," the U.N. chief said.
</P>
<P>
"The ground-breaking Declaration on the Guiding Principles of
Demand Reduction creates a balanced approach which, for the first
time, addresses the responsibility of nations where consumption is
a problem as well as that of nations where production is a
problem," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"In each case, a target must be met. By the year of 2008,
Member States should have made real progress in eliminating or
reducing significantly crops of opium poppy, coca and cannabis.
The growing trend in abuse and production of psychotrophic
substance must be reversed," the U.N. secretary-general stressed.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations International Drug Control Program has
risen to the challenge. It has shaped a balanced and global
strategy to implement the decisions that will be adopted during
the crucial three days. The new version represents a quantum leap
from the piecemeal and pilot projects of the past three decades,"
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"When we pull together from all corners of the world to try to
solve a problem, we will always succeed. Let this be one of those
occasions. It's time for all nations to say `yes' to the challenge
of working towards a drug-free world," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
