<HEADLINE> Philippines' Incoming Ruling Party Seen to Break Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' incoming ruling
party, the so-called United Opposition, is seen to break up as its
winning presidential candidate Joseph Estrada is trying to revive
his own tiny party.
</P>
<P>
President-Elect Estrada, who won the May 11 polls under the
banner of the LAMMP (Fight of Patriotic Filipino Masses) party,
confirmed Monday that the next ruling party will be his Partido ng
Masang Pilipino (PMP or Party of Filipino Masses).
</P>
<P>
The PMP is one of the three opposition parties which merged to
form the LAMMP last year in order to beat the ruling Lakas-NUCD
(National Union of Christian Democrats) party.
</P>
<P>
Estrada told reporters that the LAMMP is not a political party
since it was not even recognized by the Commission on Elections
(COMELEC) and was created only for the purpose of presenting a
unified ticket in the elections.
</P>
<P>
The LAMMP also includes the LDP (Fight of Democratic Filipinos)
and the Nationalist People's Coalition (NPC).
</P>
<P>
But the COMELEC failed to accredit the LAMMP as a party after
some leaders of the NPC withdrew from the merger.
</P>
<P>
"The election is over and so we now should stick with our own
parties," said Estrada.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said earlier that the PMP's door is open to defectors
from other parties including the present ruling party.
</P>
<P>
Estrada is to meet with LAMMP leaders to determine the fate of
the coalition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
