<HEADLINE> U.S. Lawmaker Hopes to Improve Relations With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.S. Congressman said
he hoped that the United States and China will continue to work
together to improve their relationship.
</P>
<P>
In a interview with Xinhua, Representative Lee H. Hamilton, a
Democrat from Indiana, said the two countries have made some
progress in improving the relations, although progress comes hard
and slowly.
</P>
<P>
That's why the dialogue between the presidents of the two
countries is so important, said Hamilton, Ranking Minority Member
on the House International Relations Committee, who began his term
in the House in 1965.
</P>
<P>
"President (Bill) Clinton's visit to China is very important. I think
we are seeking to place U.S.-China relations on a more normal
basis, a more solid footing," Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's terribly important for the two leaders to meet
regularly to talk about the problems that exist between the two
countries and I think the summit meetings are very helpful," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Asked about China's MFN status, the Representative said it
will eventually be approved, but it will go through a "rocky
and difficult process."
</P>
<P>
MFN is a very important symbol of the U.S.-China relationship,
he said. "If we were to defeat the MFN treatment to China, it
would send a huge signal of deterioration of U.S.-China
relations.
</P>
<P>
He said a lot of people who oppose President Clinton are using
the China policy as a means of attacking him politically and
attacking the Democratic Party, even though the president's policy
was originally established by former President Richard Nixon and
has been carried out by every president, Republican and Democrat
since the opening to China in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
On Chinese-American relations, Hamilton said, "We have many
areas where we cooperate and many areas where we do not."
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Clinton will make a reciprocal visit to
China later this month following Chinese President Jiang Zemin's
trip to the United States last fall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
