<HEADLINE> Israel Launches Campaign to Boost Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Israel launched a campaign on
Monday to boost the tourism of the country which has suffered a
setback due to the stalemate in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The campaign was started with the unveiling of a logo for the
tourism of the year 2000 with the elements of the year, the holy
land and peace on display.
</P>
<P>
The logo was displayed at an official ceremony at the foot of
the wall of Jerusalem's Old City.
</P>
<P>
The campaign is to attract more than 4 million tourists to the
country that year, or doubling the number of foreign visitors in
1997, said Tourism Minister Moshe Katsav at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Since Christianity attaches great importance to making
pilgrimages to the religious sites in Israel in 2000, Katsav said
there will be an increase in the Christian tourists' number in
that year.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Israel has invested 3 million U.S. dollars to
improve tourism infrastructure in the past four years and will
continue to invest the same amount in this field before the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the campaign goes on without any political
considerations and called for the neighbor countries to cooperate
at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
The tourism industry is a key source of Israel's revenue. But
since the Middle East peace process was stalemated a year ago,
the number of visitors has been steadily declining. 
</P>
</TEXT>
