<HEADLINE> International Ferroalloy Congress Brings China Closer to World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing three-day Eighth
International Ferroalloy Congress here has been seen by many as an
opportunity to connect Chinese ferroalloy manufacturers and
traders with the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese participants are "abroad in China," said Yang
Zhizhong, director of the Ferroalloy department of China's
Central Iron and Steel Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
China is the world's largest ferroalloy producer but, generally
speaking, its ferroalloy industry is still closed to the rest of
the world, said Zhong Zengyong, vice-president of the Chinese
Metals Society.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhong, only a few representatives attended the
last several congresses that were held in other countries.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the current congress has attracted 160
Chinese delegates, including those representing major
manufacturers. The remaining 280 participants are from 36 other
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
In the last five years, China has remained the largest
ferroalloy producer and exporter, with an annual production of 4
million to 4.3 million tons and annual exports of one million to
1.3 million tons.
</P>
<P>
A huge investment is, however, still required to upgrade
technology in energy conservation and environmental
protection. And the Chinese government is working on export
policies concerning the industry to better safeguard the interests
of Chinese exporters.
</P>
<P>
The congress opened Sunday and was organized by the Chinese
Metals Society.
</P>
<P>
Participants will discuss materials, treatment, energy-saving
technologies, environmental protection, automated control and
other topics during the meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
