<HEADLINE> Nepal to Discuss Issues with India, Bhutan: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Girija
Prasad Koirala said here Monday that he will discuss with Indian
and Bhutanese leaders bilateral issues on the sidelines of the
coming SAARC summit.
</P>
<P>
Koirala told the press at his official residence that during
the summit of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) to be held in Colombo, Sri Lanka, in July, he
will meet with Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee to
discuss the issue of Kalapani in far-western Nepal which borders
India.
</P>
<P>
He said Kalapani is Nepalese territory and his country will not
even lose one inch of the land.
</P>
<P>
He said that when Indian President K. R. Narayanan visited
Nepal in late May, they talked about the issue and the president
took a positive attitude toward solving the problem.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said high-level committees have been formed
in both countries to solve the Kalapani issue.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, he summoned Indian Ambassador to Nepal K. V. Rajan
to tell him that his statement on Kalapani is not correct.
</P>
<P>
When meeting with a Nepalese student delegation last Wednesday,
the Indian ambassador said that according to all the records
available to the Indian government, Kalapani has been on the
Indian side of the border since the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Koirala said he will also request Bhutanese King
Jigme Singye Wangchuck to resolve the refugee issue as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 Bhutanese refugees are staying in eastern Nepal
in eight U.N.-run camps after they were forced to flee Bhutan in
1989 and the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Seven rounds of ministerial talks between the two Himalayan
kingdoms have failed to produce any result. 
</P>
</TEXT>
