<HEADLINE> Blatter Elected New FIFA President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Swiss Joseph Blatter will succeed
Joao Havelange as president of the International Football
Federation (FIFA) after winning 111 votes from 191 members of FIFA
meeting here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 62-year-old secretary general of FIFA was formally elected
after his rival, Swedish Lennart Johansson, 68, announced his
withdrawal when the second round of voting began.
</P>
<P>
An two thirds absolute majority, or 128 votes, are officially
required for election in the first round.
</P>
<P>
Very excited, Blatter immediately found his daughter, Corinne,
who masterminded the campaign for her father.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing president Havelange, who supported Blatter during the
campaign, praised Johansson for showing his sportsmanship by
admitting defeat after the first round of voting.
</P>
<P>
Johansson was supported by the International Olympic Committee
president Juan Antonio Samaranch, Football King Pele, Europe (not
France) and Africa after he announced his candidacy in November
1995.
</P>
<P>
Blatter, who is a close friend of French soccer star Michel
Platini, will be the 8th president of FIFA since its creation in
1904.
</P>
<P>
He left the world with a deep impression when presiding the
World Cup lots drawing ceremony held last December in Marseille.
</P>
<P>
When he announced in Paris his candidacy for FIFA presidency in
March, he gave the following slogan: ``One football for all, and
all for football.''
</P>
<P>
"It should be above all now that the unity of football be
maintained," he said after being elected.
</P>
<P>
He proposed a closer collaboration with national football
associations, especially those most underprivileged, the
establishment of a bureau of executive committee consisting of
seven FIFA members, and the holding of annual national congresses
of the federation.
</P>
<P>
Platini, who is expected to serve as the executive director of
sports for FIFA under Blatter, said that he expects the most
difficult battles ahead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
