<HEADLINE> Israel Inner Cabinet Fails to Decide on Hamas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli inner cabinet failed
to make a decision at a meeting on Monday on whether to ban Hamas
spiritual leader Sheikh Ahmed Yassin from returning to Gaza.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister's Office said the inner cabinet will further
discuss this issue in the coming days and a decision would come
out soon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli inner cabinet consists of several key ministers and
makes decisions on important issues such as security and
defense.
</P>
<P>
Last week, several Israeli Knesset (parliament) members asked
the Defense Ministry to study the possibility of banning Yassin
from returning to Gaza, saying his current fund-raising trip to
Islamic and Arab nations has endangered Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
Foreign diplomats here said banning Yassin's return to Gaza is
not that easy and Israel has to think about the reactions from
Hamas (Islamic Resistance Movement), which is strongly opposing
the Oslo Accords and the Palestinian peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat
has reportedly told the Israeli authorities on Sunday that Israel
should not prevent Yassin from returning to Gaza.
</P>
<P>
"Yesterday I spoke with Israeli officials and told them not to
intervene...Yassin is a Palestinian and we will permit him to
return," Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Hamas officials said Sunday that a
leaflet signed by Hamas military wing Izzadin Al-Kassam
criticizing Yassin for visiting Syria and Kuwait was fabricated or
instigated by Israel or the PNA.
</P>
<P>
The leaflet distributed at An-Najah University in Nablus and
in Gaza Sunday took issue with Yassin's visit to Kuwait where
hundreds of Palestinians have been held prisoner since the 1991
Gulf War. It argued against Yassin's stop in Syria where thousands
of Sunni Muslims were killed in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
"We call on Yassin and those who accompanied him in his visit
to wake up and open their eyes, because fighters can not be bought
off with money, and fighters do not sit in front of the cameras
with oppressors," the leaflet said.
</P>
<P>
However, Hamas official Mahamoud Zahar said in Gaza on Sunday
that the leaflet is not authentic.
</P>
<P>
PNA also denied the charges on Sunday and said that the leaflet
was circulated by Palestinians opposed to Yassin's fund-raising
tour.
</P>
<P>
Yassin would reportedly cancel his trip to Libya and return to
Gaza soon via Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
