<HEADLINE> U.S. Military Intervention in Kosovo Unlikely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.S. official said on
Monday that the United States has no immediate plans to send
troops to end ethnic fighting in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
A military intervention "is not something that is on the
table," said Sandy Berger, President Bill Clinton's national
security advisor.
</P>
<P>
Berger made the remark aboard Air Force One while flying with
Clinton to New York, according to an Associated Press report.
Clinton is attending a United Nations conference on anti-narcotics.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and its allies however may reconsider a recent
decision to suspend economic sanctions against Yugoslavia in the
next few days, said Berger.
</P>
<P>
That would likely include a ban on American investment in
Yugoslavia, whose dominant republic is Serbia.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, British Prime Minister Tony Blair, whose country
holds the current presidency of the European Union, discussed the
situation in Kosovo with Clinton by phone.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the two leaders agreed to send a strong message to
Belgrade over the escalating violence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. would join Britain in seeking a resolution from the
U.N. Security Council that would authorize the use of force, if
necessary, to ease tensions in the region, reported the Cable News
Network (CNN) television on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanian separatists in Kosovo are seeking independence
from Serbia. Washington has said that it would not support an
independent Kosovo, but insist more autonomy should be given to
the ethnic Albanians, who comprise 90 percent of Kosovo's
population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
