<HEADLINE> Construction Begins on Third-Phase of Qinshan Nuclear Power Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Canadian and Chinese workers today
poured concrete into the base of the major factory building of the
nuclear power plant located in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The third phase of the nuclear power plant, which is now under
construction, includes China's first heavy water reactor for a
power station. Upon completion, the plant -- which will have a
generating capacity of 1.456 million kilowatts -- will begin
operations in February of 2003.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side signed contracts with Canadian businesses in
November of 1996 for the construction. The state development bank
also cooperated with foreign banks for loans.
</P>
<P>
China's National Nuclear Corp., East China Electric Group
Corp., Zhejiang Electric Development Corp., Shenneng Electric
Company Ltd. and Jiangsu Trust and Investment Corp. poured their
money into Qinshan No. 3 Nuclear Power Company Ltd., the legal
person of the nuclear power plant.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the State Council and neighboring Shanghai
Municipality and Jiangsu Province supported the project.
</P>
<P>
As the major contractor for the project, Atomic Energy of
Canada Limited took responsibility for the engineering design,
equipment manufacture, material, project management and personnel
training.
</P>
<P>
Chinese workers have excavated a total of 1.976 million cubic
meters of stone and earthwork for the project. The trunk road from
the plant to adjacent cities has also been finished.
</P>
<P>
The project now has a good start thanks to close cooperation
between Canadian experts and workers and Chinese workers, said
Zhang Huazhu, chairman of the board of directors of the Qinshan
No.3 Nuclear Power Company Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Zhang expressed his belief that the two sides will succeed in
building China's first heavy water reactor-equipped nuclear power
plant, which uses natural uranium rather than enriched uranium as
fuels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
