<HEADLINE> Vajpayee Rejects U.N. Security Council Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari
Vajpayee rejected Monday the U.N. Security Council resolution
adopted last Saturday which calls on India and Pakistan to stop
their nuclear and missile programs.
</P>
<P>
In his first reaction to the resolution, Vajpayee said in Rajya
Sabha, the upper house of the Indian Parliament, that decisions in
this regard would be taken by the Indian government on the basis
of its own assessments and national security.
</P>
<P>
He termed the resolution "unacceptable," saying India's nuclear
tests were necessary because of what he said the failure of a
flawed non-proliferation regime in the world.
</P>
<P>
The Indian prime minister described as "redundant" the Security
Council resolution urging India and Pakistan not to carry out any
nuclear weapon test and said New Delhi has already instituted a
voluntary moratorium.
</P>
<P>
He rejected the notion that the nuclear tests have adversely
affected either regional or global security.
</P>
<P>
He called for an earlier resumption of official talks with
Pakistan to resolve outstanding issues between the two neighbors
including Jammu and Kashmir, peace and security.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee ruled out any third party mediation in the dialogue
process and said India's proposals for modalities of talks have
been with Pakistan since January this year.
</P>
<P>
A secure and prosperous Pakistan is in India's interest, he
said, adding that India has always desired peaceful, friendly and
mutually beneficial relations with Pakistan based on confidence
and respect for each other's concerns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
