<HEADLINE> Germany Tightens Safety Checks on High-Speed Trains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Germany's rail authorities have
decided to make it routine to conduct special safety checkups on
the country's high-speed trains, officials said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The decision came after one of the trains derailed last week,
killing at least 98 people in the country's worst railroad crash
since World War II.
</P>
<P>
The checkup, in which ultrasonic equipment will be used, is to
determine whether the wheels of trains may have developed any
mechanical defects.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that a broken wheel led to the tragic derailment
which occurred last Wednesday near the northern German town of
Eschede.
</P>
<P>
The rail authorities have recalled 59 of the trains for an
ultrasonic checkup over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the German police lowered the death toll of last
week's train crash to 98 from 102 as reported earlier, citing
reasons of a duplicate count. Rescue workers are still searching
the crash site for victims.
</P>
<P>
Officials on Monday admitted that the rail crash has undermined
public trust in the country's fastest trains, which can travel at
a speed of 280 kilometers per hour.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, another train approaching Regensburg in southern
Germany was stopped by the engineer who was concerned with unusual
noises coming from the engine. About 700 passengers were
transferred to another train as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
Authorities who inspected the train confirmed the driver's
suspicions: the noises had came from the engine, but the cause was
not known. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
