<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Natural Gas to Replace Coal in Central Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Beijing will ban the burning of
coal in 105.39 square kilometers of its central districts by 2000
to reduce air pollution.
</P>
<P>
Natural gas, piped from Shaanxi and Gansu provinces as well as
the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region in northwest China, will replace
coal in 40 designated regions within the Third Ring Road,
according to the Beijing Environmental Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The use of coal is the main cause of Beijing's air pollution,
according to the bureau. Statistics show 90 percent of the city's
sulphur dioxide in the air in 1997 came from burning coal.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Beijing will popularize quality coal with a low
sulphur content and energy-saving technology outside the 40
designated regions.
</P>
<P>
After the measures are taken, Beijing expects to reduce the
release of sulphur dioxide by 125,000 tons and dust by 84,000 tons
by 2000, according to the bureau.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
