<HEADLINE> NPC, CPPCC Members Comment on Work of Supreme People's Procuratorate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme People's Procuratorate
has invited members of the country's top legislative body and
consultative body to air their views on ways to overhaul and
consolidate China's procuratorial bodies.
</P>
<P>
Tao Siju, a member of the National People's Congress (NPC)
Standing Committee, said great importance should be attached to
fair law enforcement, which is a core issue for China's political
and legal departments.
</P>
<P>
Wu Shuqing, also a member of the NPC Standing Committee, said
that China's prosecutors should establish their sense of public
service and enhance their professional skills.
</P>
<P>
Members of the National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) also aired their
opinions covering a variety of issues ranging from the
transparency of the procuratorial bodies to prosecutors' ethics.
</P>
<P>
Han Zhubin, procurator-general of the Supreme People's
Procuratorate, expressed his thanks to the members of the NPC
Standing Committee and of the CPPCC National Committee for their
candid opinions and suggestions.
</P>
<P>
He said the Supreme People's Procuratorate will dispatch 10
inspection teams to tour the country in the coming months, and
that members of NPC Standing Committee and of the CPPCC National
Committee are welcome to accompany the inspection tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
