<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Tighten Wildlife Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Monday pledged to
further tighten wildlife protection laws to deter poaching.
</P>
<P>
"We have done so for the sake of protecting our environment by
amending our Environment Quality Act 1974 twice within a short
time frame, and we will not hesitate to do likewise to protect
wildlife from poachers," Science, Technology and Environment
Minister Law Hieng Ding said.
</P>
<P>
Between January 1997 and May 1998, five major syndicates
supplying poached wildlife for exotic food were busted and fined
in courts for a total of 50,000 ringgit (about 12,515 U.S.
dollars), he said in a speech launching the Malaysian leg of the
Asia Conservation Awareness Program (ACAP) here. The speech was
read out by his deputy Abu Bakar Daud.
</P>
<P>
He said that although the fines were reasonably high compared
to past years, his ministry is seriously looking into "tightening
further the Protection of Wildlife Act to make it a deterrent to
poach."
</P>
<P>
Law called for an awareness campaign targeted at members of the
public, who are willing to pay hefty sums for such items, to
minimize consumption of threatened wildlife and products.
</P>
<P>
The ACAP is an educational program involving the public and
local non-governmental organizations like the Malaysian Nature
Society in the conservation of threatened wildlife such as tigers,
rhinos, turtles, bears and elephants.
</P>
<P>
The program is aimed at encouraging the public to stop buying
products made from endangered species and increasing their
involvement in curbing the trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
