<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Has 70% of World AIDS Cases: WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (WHO)
has expressed concern over the AIDS mortality rate in Africa
which it said has 70 percent of the 20.8 million global cases of
infection.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement, WHO Regional Director Ebrahim Samba
Monday said everyday 7,500 Africans get infected out of a global
total of 16,000 daily infections.
</P>
<P>
"The most vulnerable groups have been from Africa's most
active and productive people aged between 15 and 40. The results
have been a weakening productive base, a growing orphan
population, further strains on already under-staffed and
under-funded health services across the continent and the adverse
consequences of all these on the quality of life of Africa," said
Samba in Harare.
</P>
<P>
Samba said efforts so far made to contain the pandemic include
caring for the victims and the launching and promotion of
sensitization on safe sex.
</P>
<P>
"In spite of these efforts, the situation is worsening," Samba
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
