<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Calls for Reform Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B. J. Habibie
Monday asked the National Human Rights Committee to consider
setting up a working group on national reforms, an official said
here.
</P>
<P>
The working group will carry out the reform process in
political, economic and legal fields, Chairman of the National
Human Rights Committee Marzuki Darusman told reporters after
meeting with Habibie.
</P>
<P>
With the formation of the working group, the government will
gradually gain trust from the people, he said, adding that the
group will among other things work to free the government from
corruption, collusion and nepotism.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, President Habibie said the country needs reform
brought about through an evolution, not a revolution. He explained
that this is the way in which he intends to pursue reform,
including preparations for a general election next year.
</P>
<P>
The president noted that his government has been rushing to
implement the various reform agendas. The government intends to
complete the laws on elections and political parties by August and
hold elections in May next year.
</P>
<P>
The president also promised to stick to the economic reform
programs reached between the government and the International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting Monday, Marzuki said, the president also
indicated that the government will release more political
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The government has released four political prisoners and
dropped charges against three female activists last month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Justice Minister Muladi disclosed here Monday that a
total of 16 political prisoners will be released by the government
in the near future. 
</P>
