<HEADLINE> Two National Newspapers Organize Media Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Two Beijing-based national
newspapers, "Guangming Daily" and "Economic Daily," declared today
that they have organized newspaper groups as part of the reform of
China's media system.
</P>
<P>
Both newspapers are well-known among domestic and overseas
readers.
</P>
<P>
Founded nearly 50 years ago, the "Guangming Daily" has formed
an extensive network of news collection with more than 60 bureaus
at home and abroad. Three newspapers and three periodicals are
under the umbrella of the daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
In addition, "Guangming Daily" has started businesses in
publishing, advertising, printing, social education and
consulting.
</P>
<P>
The "Economic Daily" was founded in 1983 along with the
country's overall reform and opening-up to the outside world. It
has set up 36 reporting stations throughout the country and
another 23 overseas. There also are six subsidiary papers and
periodicals.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper also has started businesses in publishing,
advertising, printing, information services, cultural promotions
and real estate.
</P>
<P>
The founding of newspaper groups in China was started in 1995
by the "Guangzhou Daily." On May 18 the "Nanfang Daily" and
"Yangcheng Evening News" also declared that they had organized
newspaper groups.  
</P>
</TEXT>
