<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Derivatives Increase Market Stability: HK Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 8 (Xinhua) -- For a mature financial market
with depth and breadth, risk management has become an
indispensable component, Hong Kong's Financial Secretary Donald
Tsang said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the unveiling ceremony for the new corporate logo
of Hong Kong Futures Exchange, Tsang said: "A well-developed,
liquid and orderly derivatives market is essential to allow risks
to be easily transferred at market prices from one investor to
another." "This in turn offers support for trading and turnover at
the cash market and increases overall market stability and
liquidity."
</P>
<P>
"The growth of the derivatives market has fundamentally
transformed financial institutions' risk management and their
customers have been able to lower their funding costs and
structure risks to the desired level and configuration," the
official said.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out, "While we should welcome the
phenomenal growth of the derivatives market over the last two
decades, it does lead to concerns of market participants and
brings new challenges to regulators."
</P>
<P>
"Such debate is of course not unfamiliar to you who are
witnesses of the turmoil in the Asian financial market," Tsang
said.
</P>
<P>
Suggestions like downsizing the market, closing out more risky
operations and limiting trading might offer some comfort to those
who feel more at home with the traditional world of stocks and
shares, Tsang noted.
</P>
<P>
"But even they must accept that, in a free and open market,
what has to go up will go up and what must go down will go
down. For every assertion that derivatives magnify volatility,
there is an equally valid assertion that they do, in fact,
smoothen volatility," Tsang noted.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong government reiterated in a report released in
April this year its commitment to maintaining Hong Kong as an
international financial center and recognized the useful roles
that a properly-run and well-developed derivatives market plays in
this context, he added.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the government also recognized the need for
improvement in the market.
</P>
<P>
"In this connection, we welcome the initiative by the Futures
Exchange to increase transparency of the market and enhance
trading efficiency through the upgrading of its trading system and
eventual migration of the trading of the Hang Seng Index futures
contracts to the Automated Trading System," Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
The Futures Exchange trades more than 26,000 index futures
contracts a day on average and offers more than 20 products
including stock indices futures and options, currency futures and
interest rate futures to its increasingly diversified clientele.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
