<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Not Concerned Over Currency Fluctuation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEPANG (Malaysia), June 8 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said here Monday that his government is no longer
concerned about the fluctuations of the ringgit against the U.S.
dollar because the country is moving toward barter trade.
</P>
<P>
"What we want to do is to get away from the value of the
ringgit and this can be done easily by conducting trade on a
countertrade basis or through practical bartering," he told
reporters after a visit to the new Kuala Lumpur International
airport here.
</P>
<P>
"We are not very concerned anymore," Mahathir said when asked
to comment on the ringgit's further decline against the greenback
Monday morning when the local unit went below the 4 ringgit mark
to 4.15 ringgit against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
At the close Monday, the ringgit ended at 3.9950/005 to the
greenback against 3.9700/900 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Malaysia is expected to conduct trade through the
countertrade or barter trade system in an effort to reduce
dependence on foreign currency usage, especially the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
He noted that even before this, the ringgit went down to 4.8 to
one U.S. dollar at one time, then recovered before it slid again.
</P>
<P>
"This is a play which we have no control of," he said,
stressing that the government would be working out how much the
country was exporting and how much it was importing in terms of
goods.
</P>
<P>
"The value of goods does not appreciate or depreciate whether
the ringgit changes in value," Mahathir said. He cited as an
example the value of a computer costing 700 U.S. dollars and a ton
of palm oil costing the same, noting that their value would be
unchanged even if the ringgit went up or down.
</P>
<P>
"When the ringgit depreciates or appreciates, it is 700 U.S.
dollars, so it makes no difference anyway," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
