<HEADLINE> World Bank Aid to Angola Tops $130m </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has offered a total
of 130 million U.S. Dollars in the 10 aid programs for Angola so
far, a World Bank official has said.
</P>
<P>
Philip Civusu, World Bank representative to Angola, said in
central Angola's Calombolaca City that the first of the 10
programs aided by the bank started in 1992, which also heralded
the Bank's assistance in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said the World Bank has pooled 135 million U.S. Dollars for
the programs which would take 270 million Dollars altogether as
planned, an Angola News Agency story said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Despite all the interruptions by the civil war in the country,
construction of the programs has gone half way.
</P>
<P>
The programs under World Bank financial aid mainly cover the
building of the tap water systems and the basic sanitation
facilities in Luanda and Benguela, the rehabilitation of the
power supply system in central Angola, and of four major roads,
among others.
</P>
<P>
Most of Angola's 18 provinces, Civusu said, have received aid
from the bank, with Angola social aid fund covering nine
provinces in the country.
</P>
<P>
Civusu said that the World Bank has helped train cadres for
Angola and offered technical support for the modernization of its
financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Namibe, Lobito and Luanda, three of the major ports of the
country have been upgraded with new equipment provided by the
bank, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
