<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BIS President on Medium-term Financial Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BASLE, Switzerland, June 8 (Xinhua) -- It is essential to meet
certain preconditions in order to preserve the stability of the
domestic and international financial system in the medium-term,
President of the Bank for International Settlements (BIS) Alfons
Verplaetse said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The Asian crisis has served as a painful reminder that the
potential benefits of open and global financial markets will be
realized only if certain preconditions are met," said Verplaetse at
the 68th annual meeting of the BIS.
</P>
<P>
Verplaetse, who is also chairman of the BIS Board of Directors,
said the public policy should, over the next few years, focus on
making progress in three interrelated areas: transparency,
incentives for market discipline and prudential regulations and
supervision.
</P>
<P>
"With respect to transparency, central bankers have
increasingly emphasized that the effectiveness of domestic
policy-making depends crucially on markets clearly understanding
our objectives, our strategies and even our operational
procedures," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Transparency is equally vital in the private sector if lenders
and borrowers are to make informed decisions about the riskiness
of their prospective activities.
</P>
<P>
Public disclosure of meaningful data is a necessary
condition to ensure a proper degree of market discipline, but it
is not sufficient.
</P>
<P>
Another necessary condition is that the market should also be
capable of monitoring effectively and interpreting appropriately
the information that is already available.
</P>
<P>
"Creating the right incentive structure for profitable, yet
prudent, financial decisions is a second major policy challenge,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
In the light of the role played by the international interbank
market in the Asian arena, a careful assessment of the effect of
implicit and explicit safety nets on the behavior of both
creditors and borrowers is called for.
</P>
<P>
As part of this review, consideration should be given to the
impact on market attitudes of official liquidity support for
countries in crisis.
</P>
<P>
"A review of liquidity support packages is, in any event,
necessary since the continuous growth in their size threatens to
outstrip available resources. This raises once again the
long-standing question of the appropriate balance between
financing and adjustment," he added.
</P>
<P>
The third item on the medium-term agenda should be to further
enhance the regulatory and supervisory framework.
</P>
<P>
The core principles for effective banking supervision unveiled
last year are a landmark achievement in this regard, the president
said.
</P>
<P>
Work is also under way to develop an understanding on sound
practices in other areas, with a view to international adoption in
a similar way. As experience with implementing the core principles
grows, there will also be the opportunity for new lessons to be
learned and for the principles to be adapted accordingly.
</P>
<P>
It is through such processes that regulation and supervision
will continue to be kept up to date in a rapidly evolving world.
</P>
<P>
"If headway can be made in each of the three areas I have just
singled out, and if the underlying payments and legal
infrastructure can also be strengthened, a more efficient as well
as a more stable financial system can be constructed over the
medium term," Verplaetse said. "This challenge goes far beyond the
BIS, and those who regularly meet here, to the whole of the
international community."
</P>
<P>
"There are difficult steps that still need to be taken by
national legislators around the world if the resilience of our
financial system is to be further reinforced and the likelihood of
future crises reduced," he pointed out. "What ultimately remains
to be seen is whether enough political will can be mustered to do
what needs to be done." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minister Sees Weakness in Malaysia's Internal System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's internal system has
weaknesses and should be rectified particularly during the current
economic slowdown, Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister
Anwar Ibrahim said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"If firm measures are necessary, we will take them. If such
measures are necessary to guarantee the strength of our financial
institutions, we will adopt these measures so that they (financial
institutions) do not become paralyzed," he was quoted by the
Malaysian national news agency Bernama as saying in the
southeastern state of Johor.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said that even though Malaysia remains firm in calling
for reforms to the international monetary system and uncertain
market conditions, it also needs to realize that not everything
that is happening in the countries of this region is the result of
an unjust financial system.
</P>
<P>
"There are also internal ills and problems that need to be
corrected. If we refuse to accept the facts just like the past
leadership of Indonesia which refused to accept, then the people
will rise and demand changes in a harsh way," he was quoted as
saying when opening the Johor UMNO (United Malays National
Organization) Convention there.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said Malaysians should be grateful that the country need
not seek help from the International Monetary Fund as the
government has already taken the necessary measures to handle the
economic problems.
</P>
<P>
In this respect Malaysia needs strength and unity among the
people in facing the economic problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We should make the corrections with determination and continue
reforming the culture of our society in dealing with the question
of the economy and management," said Anwar, who is also deputy
president of the ruling UMNO.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would step up efforts to ensure
confidence particularly among investors in economic revival so
that the economy would move forward more rapidly.
</P>
<P>
"While we demand changes and reformation in the international
financial system, the nation should also defend its policies which
have served it well and also make appropriate renewals and changes
so that it does not deviate from the principle of justice," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was of the view that the international monetary system's
present form and methods favor rich nations, making it possible
for the currency trading system to be manipulated and speculation
to occur while small and developing nations have to put up with
the present regulations.
</P>
<P>
"We should not budge from our stand that part of our problems
and those of developing nations stemmed from an uncertain and
unjust financial and market system," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
