<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Adopts New Sanctions Against Serbia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) foreign ministers,
meeting in Luxembourg on Monday, agreed to apply a ban on new
investments in Serbia to protest against its military action on
ethnic Albanians in its Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
"The council has today adopted a common position for a ban on
new investments in Serbia. The Commission will act rapidly to make
the necessary proposal for implementation," the 15 ministers said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
They also stated that the union "remains ready to press ahead
with other measures against Belgrade if the authorities there fail
to halt their excessive use of force and to take the steps needed
for genuine political progress."
</P>
<P>
Monday's move by the EU marks a return to a tougher stance
against the Yugoslav Federation for the actions it has taken in the
Albanian-majority province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"Modern Europe will not tolerate the full might of an army
being used against civilian centers," said British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook who was chairing the European Union general
affairs council.
</P>
<P>
Hans van den Broek, European Commissioner for Foreign Affairs,
said the EU should send a strong message stating that what was
happening in Kosovo was "horrible and unacceptable".
</P>
<P>
The EU foreign ministers also called on the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization to accelerate its evaluation of military
options to stop the Kosovo violence they fear may lead to another
Balkan war.
</P>
<P>
They had agreed to freeze all of Belgrade's state-held funds
abroad.
</P>
<P>
An arms embargo and a ban on the delivery of police equipment
is already in force against Slobodan Milosevic's government.
</P>
</TEXT>
