<HEADLINE> Chile-China Agro-Business Seminar Opens in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 8 (Xinhua) -- A four-day seminar on investment
in agro-processing and forestry between China and Chile opened
here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony, Chinese Vice-Minister of
Agriculture Wan Baorui said that both China and Chile are major
farming countries.
</P>
<P>
China is developing toward the goal of building a modern
agricultural nation which has multiple aspects and combines
production with processing and marketing, he said. Reaching that
goal will open a great vista for enhancing agricultural
cooperation between China and other countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said Chile, as an export-oriented agricultural state, has
vast superiority in farm produce processing, paving the way for
mutual supplements. The current seminar provides Chinese and
Chilean agricultural entrepreneurs with an opportunity for
strengthening mutual understanding and cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jean Jacques Duhart, vice-minister of agriculture of Chile,
said China is his country's sixth largest agricultural
partner. There are many agricultural areas remaining to be tapped
for enterprises of both countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chile is optimistic about investing in agricultural projects in
China, a clear sign of confidence in the prospects of China and
the Pacific region, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the seminar, officials of the Chilean foreign investment
committee and other specialized organizations briefed 150 Chinese
entrepreneurs about agricultural and forest development in Chile,
the investment environment there and preferential terms offered by
Chilian government. The Chinese Ministry of Agriculture and the
Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation will also
discuss agricultural development and investment policies of China
at the seminar.
</P>
<P>
Chile is China's fourth largest trade partner in Latin
America with a trade volume of 977 million U.S. dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, China had built 14 enterprises in
Chile with a total investment of 26 million U.S. dollars. The only
Chilean enterprise opened in China was Corpora Food and Beverage
Company, with an investment of 10 million U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
