<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Duma Chief Warns Against NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Russia's speaker of the lower house
of parliament warned Monday that NATO's inclusion of former Soviet
Union countries would harm European security and prompt Moscow to
reconsider its treaty with the group.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the fourth session of the Russian-French
Parliamentary Commission in St. Petersburg, State Duma Chairman
Gennady Seleznyov expressed his apprehension over "the activity of
NATO in Europe."
</P>
<P>
NATO has decided in its first round of enlargement toward
Eastern Europe to take in Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic
and intends to continue the move to include former Soviet nations
in defiance of Russia's opposition.
</P>
<P>
Moscow believes "drawing the former USSR republics into the
alliance's sphere of interests can lead to negative consequences
in Europe and a drastic revision of the Russian-NATO Treaty,"
Seleznyov said, in reference to the pact reached last year aimed
at promoting bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The French parliament will discuss Hungary, Poland and the
Czech Republic's NATO membership in two days, an issue in which
Seleznyov urged considering Russia's concerns.
</P>
<P>
On the enlargement of the European Union, Seleznyov said Russia
welcomes the move but opposes double standards regarding the
Baltic states grouping Latvia, Estonia and Lithuania, which want
to distance themselves from Russia and seek integration into the
E.U. and NATO.
</P>
<P>
For Russia itself, the Duma speaker said, it is "not prepared
yet either morally or economically to become a member of the
European community, but closer ties between the East and Europe,
Russia and Europe are irrevocable."
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary commission, established in 1995, was to
discuss at the two-day session issues of European security and
Russia's integration into the international community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
