<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somalia's Baidoa in Aidid's Hands Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Hussein Mohamed Aidid's men
finally regained control of the troubled town of Baidoa, 250 west
of the capital, Sunday, reports reaching here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to VHF radio reports, the heaviest fighting had
occurred at the former presidential palace and the airstrip of
the town where the Rahanwein Resistance Army (RRA) had pit
against the forces of Hussein Aidid who lost the town early
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses said the corpses of 29 civilians and seven
militiamen were found in the streets of Baidoa, with six of the
dead killed as they tried to escape in a bus leaving the town
because of the fighting.
</P>
<P>
Seven more of the dead bodies were identified as the
militiamen of Aidid.
</P>
<P>
The RRA spokesman, Mohamed Ail Aden Qalinle, admitted the fall
of the town to Aidid's men Monday. However, he said his forces
still control the airport of the town and Daynunay village, north
of the town, a claim denied by travelers reaching Mogadishu and
Aidid's militia commanders.
</P>
<P>
In another fierce fighting, about a hundred heavily armed
militiamen from the RRA have also stormed into the town of Bur
Hakaba, 40 Km south of Baidoa on the road to Mogadishu Sunday as
Aidid's men have retaken control of Baidoa.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the town said the fighting has been the most
devastating as a lot of looting, killing of civilians and
innumerable destruction had occurred.
</P>
<P>
The town of Bur Hakaba is inhabited by the Elay sub-clan of
Rahanwein loyal to Aidid's faction.
</P>
<P>
Early Sunday afternoon, Aidid's men have been summoned to help
Bur Hakaba by the fleeing people. About 10 battle wagons and
mearly 150 infantry militiamen were dispatched to fight the RRA
in Bur Hakaba who were driven out of the town early Sunday
evening.
</P>
<P>
The looted properties include the VHF radio of the town, the
market and several business stores, all owned by non-combatant
civilians.
</P>
<P>
Despite sporadic fighting occurring outside Baidoa Monday, the
town appears clam, but it is getting tense as tens of thousands
of people have fled the town for safety to the neighboring
relatively safer areas.
</P>
<P>
Both the towns of Baidoa and Bur Hakaba have been seriously
hit and damaged by the fighting which is said to be the most
serious since Aidid has inherited the position of his late
father, late General Mohamed Farah Aidid in August 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
