<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Factfile of New FIFA President Sepp Blatter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Following is a factfile of the career
of Sepp Blatter, who elected FIFA president on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Born: Visp, Switzerland, March 10, 1936
</P>
<P>
Education: College de Sion and St. Maurice; University of
Lausanne: Bachelor of business administration and economics from
the Faculty of Law
</P>
<P>
1962-63: Amateur player for FC Salgesch soccer club
</P>
<P>
1964: Appointed general secretary Swiss Ice Hockey Federation
</P>
<P>
1970: Director sports timing and public relations for Longines,
involved in organisation of the 1972 and 1976 Olympics Games.
</P>
<P>
1975: Appointed FIFA's director technical development programmes
putting president Joao Havelange's projects (under-21, under-17
world competitions) into motion.
</P>
<P>
1981: November: Appointed FIFA General Secretary
</P>
<P>
1990: Appointed FIFA chief executive officer
</P>
<P>
1994: Awarded Olympic Order
</P>
<P>
1998: March 27: Declares intention to run as FIFA president.
</P>
<P>
1998: June 8: Defeats UEFA president Lennart Johansson to become
FIFA president.
</P>
<P>
Other facts: Is also president of the Sion bid to host the
2006 Winter Olympics. As a teenager worked as a concierge at the
hotel Beau Site in Zermatt. Later became head of public relations
for the Valais tourist board. Has received numerous awards
including, Knight of the Kingdom of Pahang from Malaysia; Runzi
Foundation Award (the highest award given out in Valais, his home
canton); honorary citizen of Texas. Is an active member of the
Swiss Association of Sports Writers. In 1971 he was named
President of the World Society of Friends of Suspenders. The
society, formed by a group of 120 men from 16 countries, regret
women replacing suspender belts with pantyhose. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Banks Urged to Prepare for New Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Singapore, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Deputy Prime Minister
Lee Hsien Loong Monday urged the country's banks to prepare for
fresh challenges and opportunities while combating adverse effects
of the regional crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Even as banks in Singapore draw lessons from the regional
crisis and address pressing short-term contingencies, they must
build on their strengths and prepare for fresh challenges and
opportunities after the crisis is over," Lee said in a speech at
the 25th anniversary dinner of the Association of Banks in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
"The right approach is to accept the risks but manage them
carefully and build up strong capital as a buffer against
adversity," he said, noting that Singapore banks "have established
a modest but growing presence in the region which will stand them
in good stead when these economies recover."
</P>
<P>
"Singapore's banking system is sound," he said, referring to
its strong capital adequacy ratios and good credit ratings and
avoidance of excessive credit growth and risk concentrations.
</P>
<P>
He conceded however that Singapore banks have been scathed by
the regional crisis, mentioning the sharp decline in bank earnings
last year and the shrinking loan demand this year.
</P>
<P>
"An early rebound in bank profits is unlikely," he concluded.
</P>
<P>
He praised the banks for having not stopped lending and
investing in the region and for seeking new growth opportunities
abroad. "If they had forgone these opportunities altogether, they
would have failed to diversify their sources of growth and been
forced to accept the constraints of the domestic economy," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Not diversifying gradually out of Singapore, they would have
been unable to hedge against ups and downs in the Singapore
economy itself, which no matter how skillful our economic
management can never be eliminated," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the achievements made by Singapore banks, Lee said, "High
growth figures by themselves do not prove success as a financial
center." "Rapid expansion, in the absence of proper controls and
adequate supervision, can be a recipe for disaster, as the
regional crisis has vividly illustrated."
</P>
<P>
He said the Monetary Authority of Singapore has decided to take
several steps for Singapore's banking system "to thrive and grow
in this bracing environment."
</P>
<P>
They include raising bank disclosure norms to international
standard, adopting risk-focused approach to bank examination,
lowering banks' minimum cash balance, gradually opening up the
financial sector to greater foreign competition and building up
domestic institutions to ensure the stability of the country's
banking system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
