<HEADLINE> Czech Warplanes Collide, Showering Debris Over City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, June 8 (Xinhua) - Two Czech air force jets collided
on Monday showering debris into a residential area, setting cars
on fire and injuring civilians.
</P>
<P>
The air force spokesman Peter Fajl said in a statement that the
two Soviet-made MiG-21s crashed as a result of bad weather
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The wreckage from one of the planes fell into the parking
lot of a residential complex in the suburb of Vltava in the
southern city of Ceske Budejovice.
</P>
<P>
The second plane fell into a nearby field. The three airmen,
two pilots and a crewman, ejected successfully from their planes
and were being examined in hospital.
</P>
<P>
A video of the scene broadcast by a local TV showed many cars on
fire and heavy smoke coming from the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
Three civilians were reportedly injured. Two of them were
examined and released from a nearby hospital, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
No further information was provided by the air force on the
third casualty.
</P>
<P>
The Czech air force has lost several of its Soviet-made
aircraft in accidents in the past few years. 
