<HEADLINE> New York Philharmonic to Make Debut in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The oldest symphony orchestra in
the United States, the New York Philharmonic, will make its debut
in China with concerts on June 23 and 24.
</P>
<P>
Beijing will be the last stop of the orchestra's eight-city
Asia tour which includes the Japanese cities of Fukui, Yokohama,
Omiya and Tokyo as well as Manila and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Music director Kurt Masur will lead the orchestra during
the tour and the grand finale which will take place at the Great
Hall of the People.
</P>
<P>
The New York Philharmonic has a long history of touring
beginning with its 1882 tour of the United States. Since its
founding in 1842, the orchestra has performed in 352 cities in 52
countries on five continents. The present tour is the orchestra's
second in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The orchestra's upcoming China tour is part of the recent
cultural exchanges between China and the United States. Last month
the Cleveland Orchestra performed in Shanghai and Beijing, and
Chinese President Jiang Zemin was among its audience.
</P>
<P>
In early July, the 600-year-old drama "Peony Pavilion," dubbed
as China's Romeo and Juliet, will be presented at the Lincoln
Center in New York by the Shanghai Kunju Opera Troupe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
