<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania Concerned About Bloodshed in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Foreign Minister Paskal
Milo Monday expressed grave concern over the bloodshed in Kosovo
in the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Balkan Foreign Ministerial Meeting starting
Monday moring in Istanbul, Milo said that the violence in Kosovo
has resulted in deaths of innocent civilians and posed a threat to
the security of the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
He said that a refugee influx, as a result of the bloody
clashes in the Yugoslav province, might bring a seriously negative
impact on peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Up to now around twenty thousand refugees have already
entered Albania, and more than five thousand have left for
Montenegro," he said.
</P>
<P>
Milo described the sufferings of ethnic Albanians living in
Kosovo as that experienced by people of Bosnia-Herzegovina in the
past.
</P>
<P>
Bloody clashes have been continuing since February in Kosovo
between the Serbian police and ethnic Albanians who demand
independence from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Milo called on the Balkan countries and international
community to take urgent and effective measures to end the
bleeding there.
</P>
<P>
It was noticed that Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin
Jovanovic, who also delivered a speech at the meeting, refrained
from taking up the situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The current bloodshed in Kosovo also created tensions between
Albania and Yugoslavia which have long been at odds over the
status of ethnic Albanians in the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
