<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Chief Executive Meets European Parliament Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR) Tung Chee Hwa met with a
visiting delegation of the European Parliament at his office here
Monday and briefed them on the latest developments in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed a number of issues, ranging from
the evolution of democracy and the economy in Hong Kong to the
SAR's future links with Europe.
</P>
<P>
On the development of democracy in the SAR, Tung noted that the
democratic evolutionary process is enshrined in the Basic Law,
which sets a 10-year timetable for respective elections of the
chief executive and the legislature.
</P>
<P>
"The development of democracy must comply with the timetable
set out in the Basic Law. The Basic Law is our constitution and
was written after four years' consultation and should not be
amended lightly," he said.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating that Hong Kong is going through a difficult period
of economic adjustment, the chief executive noted that years of
high property prices, high wages and negative interest rates had
resulted in a bubble economy.
</P>
<P>
"We are experiencing a credit crunch which has worsened because
of the fear of an attack on the linked rate (between the Hong Kong
dollar and the U.S. dollar). Tourism and consumer spending have
also taken a downturn," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's economy needs to be corrected if we are to regain
our competitiveness," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Tung explained that because of the currency board system, Hong
Kong could not resort to monetary measures to inflate its economy.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government had foreseen difficulties ahead when drawing
up the 1998/99 budget early this year and therefore introduced tax
reductions and expenditure increases totaling 53 billion HK
dollars (6.8 billion U.S. dollars) or 4 percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
"This has been done well within the principle of prudent
financial management," Tung said, adding that it would take time
for these fiscal stimuli to take effect.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive expressed optimism about Hong Kong's
future, saying its economic fundamentals remain sound and economic
development on the Chinese mainland is going well.
</P>
<P>
Turning to Europe, Tung said that during recent visits to the
continent, he was impressed by the achievements of the European
Union in its convergence on the euro and in other areas.
</P>
<P>
"This will help improve efficiency in trade," he said, adding
that Hong Kong would have to be prepared for the euro as it would
have implications on the management of Hong Kong's reserves, the
third largest in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
