<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt Asked to Allocate $10m on Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has been
asked to allocate 10 Million U.S. Dollars in the 1998/99 budget
to be presented at parliament Thursday, to market the east
African country in the world.
</P>
<P>
"The 10 million Dollars sought will jump-start the economy as
early as the end of this year as the tourism infrastructure is
already in place but hampered by a poor image abroad," local
reports Monday quoted Sam Mwaura, the chairman of the Kenya
Association of Tour Operators, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Tourism Board (KTB) now also proposes to take over
the running of all tourist promotion offices abroad and close
inefficient ones in a bid to revamp the industry, the country's
largest foreign exchange earner.
</P>
<P>
"We have had very little cash for marketing since KTB was
launched (two years ago) and we need a significant allocation to
make an impact abroad," said Jim Flannery, the acting chief
executive of the board.
</P>
<P>
However, the tourism players will not know if the request has
been accepted until June 11 when the budget is read, according to
the reports.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 Kenya Economic Survey issued by the government in May
describes 1997 as "a poor tourism year", when incomes from the
tourism fell by 11.6 percent from 474 million Dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Hotel occupancy in April/May this year has dropped to 20
percent from 60 to 70 percent during the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, the Kenya Tourism Board launched a
one-million-Dollar marketing drive in Europe, targeting an
estimated 40 million magazine readers in Switzerland, France,
Germany and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The promotion includes a poster campaign in 15,000 spots in
Switzerland and a plan to airlift 15 travel writers and travel
agents from Europe to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
"We expect to go on for another three months and incorporate a
further 50 million Shillings (703,650 Dollars ) from tourist
industry players in cash and kind," said Flannery.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mwaura stressed Kenya's marketing drive would not
be effective without an equal guarantee to security in the
country, especially at the coast where 80 percent of Kenya's
800,000 tourists visit.
</P>
<P>
"Marketing as a priority can only work when security is
assured," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Kenya recorded all-time lows in occupancy -- averaging 20
percent -- at popular coast hotels and staff layoffs placed at
more than 70,000 countrywide last year.
</P>
<P>
Layoffs in the tourism sector is expected to rise to 200,000
by August this year unless tourist arrivals improve. 
</P>
</TEXT>
