<HEADLINE> Forum Held on China's First High-Speed Railway Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- A group of railway experts and
government officials from China, France, Japan, Germany and Italy
attended a weekend forum on the Beijing-Shanghai high-speed
railway line held in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The event was part of the activities hosted by Shanghai for an
international railway equipment exhibition June 2-6.
</P>
<P>
During the forum, Chinese experts briefed participants on the
operation of the existing Beijing-Shanghai railway line, and the
necessity and significance of building a high-speed railway line
between the two cities.
</P>
<P>
Foreign participants discussed the development of high-speed
railways in their respective countries and showed strong interest
in construction of a Beijing-Shanghai high-speed railway line.
</P>
<P>
The projected high-speed Beijing-Shanghai railway line will run
through Tianjin Municipality and the provinces of Hebei, Shandong,
Anhui and Jiangsu and end in Shanghai. The line will be 1,300
kilometers (km) with a designed speed of 350 km per hour.
</P>
<P>
The high-speed railway line will be dual-track, electrified and
will be used only for passenger traffic. The cost is expected to
be 100 billion yuan and introduce internationally advanced
technology, equipment and management expertise.
</P>
<P>
The high-speed railway line has been written into the overall
planning of railway construction in China from 1998 to 2002.
Construction will begin in 2000.
</P>
<P>
About 4,400 km of high-speed railway lines have been built in
the world, with Japan constructing the world's first high-speed
railway line in 1964.
</P>
<P>
China plans to pump 245 billion yuan into railway construction
over the next five years to extend the existing railway system by
5,340 kilometers. The nation's current operational railway mileage
stands at 66,000 kilometers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
