<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Hits 140 Yen For First Time in Seven Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar hit the
psychologically important level of 140 yen in Tokyo Monday for the
first time in seven years due to the sluggish Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was quoted at 140.54-57 yen at 5 p.m., up from
140.26-29 yen at 9 a.m. and 139.80-90 yen last Friday in New York.
</P>
<P>
During the day, the dollar hit a high of 140.73 yen, a level
last seen in Tokyo on June 19, 1991, when it went as high as
141.13 yen.
</P>
<P>
Verbal yen-support by Japanese government officials failed to
discourage players from buying the dollar against the yen at the
higher levels, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
They said the yen is expected to continue to weaken because Japan's
economy remains sluggish, while the United States is experiencing
brisk growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
