<HEADLINE> World Cup Prompts TV Sales in Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds customers are crowding
electronics shops these days in the capital city of this South
Asian nation to buy television sets, to watch the World Cup which
is slated to be kicked off in Paris in only two days.
</P>
<P>
"Demand for black and white televisions increased by three
times in recent weeks due to World Cup soccer," a shop-owner said.
</P>
<P>
People from the middle-and-low-income groups usually buy black
and white televisions, while affluent customers are looking for
big-screen color ones of famous brands.
</P>
<P>
Some importers and retailers have offered special discount on
televisions on the eve of the World Cup, ranging between 10 and 15
percent for black and white ones and 5 to 10 percent for color
ones depending on brand and size.
</P>
<P>
The buying spree of television sets might continue till the
final match of the tournament, shopkeepers said.
</P>
<P>
As loadshedding is common in the city, particularly in hot
summer, young football fans are taking power generators on a
rental basis to ensure uninterrupted entertainment.
</P>
<P>
"We are afraid of power disruption, therefore, we procured a
generator," said Mainuddin, Rafiq, Shiplu and Shoeb, who organized
a sporting club in the city with a video projector to facilitate
local people to watch the matches.
</P>
<P>
The Dhaka Electric Supply Authority has taken special
arrangements to ensure uninterrupted power supply during the
matches between June 10 and July 12, by asking big power
consumers, such as factories and companies, to shut down for six
hours from 5 p.m. to 11 p.m. every day.
</P>
<P>
"There will be at least 13 percent production loss if we close
for six hours a day," the manager of a company said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, shops were demanded to stop business by 7 o'clock in
the evening. The sales turnover had fallen by up to 60 percent, as
"most customers prefer the evening time for shopping," shopkeepers
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
