<HEADLINE> Clinton's China Tour to Push Partnership, U.S. Ambassador Says (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton's
upcoming visit to China will serve to "further the constructive
strategic partnership" between the two countries, U.S. ambassador
to China James Sasser said here today.
</P>
<P>
There will be "more partnership" between the United States and
China in the 21st century, and this partnership will become even
stronger, said the 62-year ambassador who came to China in
February of 1996.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Sasser said that the June 25-July
3 China trip, the first by a U.S. president in almost a decade and
the first by a Democratic Party president in history, may be as
successful as that of the U.S. tour late last year by Chinese
President Jiang Zemin for this visit is based on the success of
the previous one.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of visits between the two leaders will help
further the concept of strategic partnership between the most
developed country and the largest developing nation, Sasser said.
</P>
<P>
Citing this strategic partnership in the concerted efforts in
the U.N. Security Council on the control of nuclear proliferation
in South Asia and on the Korean peninsula issue, the ambassador
explained that the two countries share joint interests and work
closely on international issues.
</P>
<P>
Sasser attributed the success of the partnership to the "wisdom
of the top leaders and the friendship forged between them," and
the respect they show for each other.
</P>
<P>
This will be the longest single-country trip for Clinton in six
years, he said, adding that the president will be pleased to have
a welcoming ceremony in the square outside the eastern gate of the
Great Hall of the People, adjacent Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Sasser went on to say, Clinton and Jiang and
other Chinese leaders will discuss bilateral relations, the
expansion of bilateral economic and trade cooperation and human
rights.
</P>
<P>
The issue of how to reduce nuclear danger in South Asia and in
the whole world also will be one of the primary international
topics, he said.
</P>
<P>
When Jiang visited many U.S. cities last year, Americans saw a
"smiling and friendly" president representing the new China which
left a favorable impression, the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Sasser said Clinton will bring a great number of news people
with him during the China trip and, through the media, Americans
will see "a China opened up by Deng Xiaoping, its fast growing
economy and the image of a major power in the 21st century."
</P>
</TEXT>
