<HEADLINE> HK New Customhouse to Facilitate Trade of Container Cargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The foundation stone was laid
Monday for a new Customhouse in Kwai Chung container terminals to
facilitate cargo clearance.
</P>
<P>
"This new Customhouse will centralize most of our offices and
facilities relating to containerized cargo under one roof, and
will help speed up cargo clearance," Commissioner of Customs and
Excise Lawrence Li Shu-fai said.
</P>
<P>
More importantly, he noted, the new establishment would enable
his department to fulfil its commitment to facilitating trade.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has been ranked the world's busiest container port
for six years in a row, with the bulk of the containerized cargo
handled by the existing eight terminals in Kwai Chung.
</P>
<P>
The new Customhouse in Kwai Chung, which will be 10 stories
high and have a gross floor area of 21,657 square meters, is
scheduled for completion in August 2001.
</P>
<P>
The building will accommodate a number of commands, including
the Ship Search and Cargo Command, the Marine and Land Enforcement
Command, the Dutiable Commodities Administration, the Supplies
Section and Dog Unit.
</P>
<P>
The year 1998 seems to be "a very significant year for us," the
commissioner said, adding other projects would be coming on
stream shortly.
</P>
<P>
"These include our new responsibilities at the new airport at
Chek Lap Kok, which would come into operation in July. We have
already started moving there and we shall have new equipment and
facilities to enable us to ensure that the airport functions
well," Li said.
</P>
<P>
The Customs is also planning a new Headquarters Tower in North
Point, Hong Kong Island.  
</P>
</TEXT>
