<HEADLINE> Blatter Becomes FIFA President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Sepp Blatter of Switzerland succeeded
Joao Havelange as FIFA president on Monday when his only rival
Lennart Johansson of Sweden withdrew after a first round of voting.
</P>
<P>
Blatter, the FIFA general secretary, gained 111 votes to UEFA
president Johansson's 80 in the vote but was 17 short of the
two-thirds majority required for outright victory.
</P>
<P>
Johansson conceded before the second round of voting.
</P>
<P>
Blatter thanked Johansson for stepping down.
</P>
<P>
"This shows not only your great personality but you're fair and
you're realistic," Blatter said.
</P>
<P>
He called on the FIFA members to close ranks and work for the
future of the game.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to thank all of you, those who voted for me and
those who did not vote for me, because we are in a democracy. The
great thing to do is to unite the family," he added.
</P>
<P>
"I promise to work for football, for the good of our great
family," he went on.
</P>
<P>
"I am a servant I don't have personal ambition," he said and
added he would work for "continuity on the right lines".  
</P>
