<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's China Tour to Push Partnership, U.S. Ambassador Says (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During Jiang's U.S. trip, Sasser said, the two presidents
agreed to set up offices in each other's capitals to exchange
information and intensify the fight against drug trafficking and
international crimes.
</P>
<P>
The two also agreed to promote dialogues on the rule of law,
and to encourage exchanges and contacts between law professors and
workers of the two nations, he said.
</P>
<P>
As for problems between the two nations, he said, differences
have been talked about too much or even exaggerated, and bilateral
cooperation and exchanges have not been talked about enough.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said the United States is the second largest
investor in China, and the largest market for Chinese goods. And
personnel contacts and economic and trade cooperation are on the
rise between the two nations, he added.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of Chinese students and scholars are now
studying in the United States, he added, and a great number of
American firms are doing business in China.
</P>
<P>
Over the long haul, the ambassador said, leaders and persons of
insight have come to learn that mutually beneficial cooperation
between the United States and China is important for international
stability and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
As China is becoming more powerful, it will play a greater role
in the international arena in the upcoming century and the
U.S.-China partnership will exert more impact, he said.
</P>
<P>
On his personal contribution to U.S.-China relations, Sasser
said since he assumed office two years ago as ambassador that he
has done his best to help leaders of both countries reduce
misunderstanding and to narrow cultural and social differences.
</P>
<P>
He said the two countries are economically supplementary and
the two people would like to "get along well and work closely"
with each other.
</P>
<P>
The United States wants to see a more-developed China and more
progress for China's entry into the World Trade Organization, he
said, adding that it also wants more bilateral cooperation in the
control of nuclear proliferation and weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
As for the U.S. Congress, he said that more than 100
congressmen visited China last year and that the majority of them
had a positive reaction of the country, whose economic progress
and people's energy had left a deep impression on them.
</P>
<P>
On the transfer of U.S. missile technology to China, he said
the launching of U.S. satellites by China had been permitted by
the U.S. government and the allegation that there is no concrete
proof that these launchings violate U.S. law.
</P>
<P>
On the South Asia situation, he said India and Pakistan should
be the signatory countries of the nuclear test ban treaty and the
nuclear non-proliferation treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
