<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BIS Considers 1997/98 Year of Good and Bad News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BASLE, Switzerland, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The financial year from
April 1997 to March 1998 has been a year of both good and bad
news, the Bank for International Settlements (BIS) said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Growth in most industrial countries is included among the
positive developments, the Basle-based BIS said in its 68th annual
report.
</P>
<P>
The darker elements in the year include the failure of the
Japanese economy to respond to repeated policy initiatives, and
the fear that the financial crisis in East Asia would spread to
the whole region and affect other economies.
</P>
<P>
The growth rates in industrial countries have either remained
at high levels or are starting to build significant momentum,
within the general context of continued low inflation.
</P>
<P>
The performance of the United States economy last year was
exceptional by international as well as historical
standards. Despite the real appreciation of the dollar, the volume
of exports grew by nearly 16 percent, raising the U.S. share of
world exports to a 20-year high.
</P>
<P>
In continental Europe, the smoothness of the path of transition
to the euro has also been remarkable and welcome.
</P>
<P>
In addition, structural reforms and more disciplined policies
have generated more solid growth in Latin America, many countries
in Eastern Europe and significant parts of Africa.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said, while growth in Japan had been the
highest among major countries in 1996 and output was still
expanding briskly during the first quarter of 1997, activity
stagnated for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
"The crisis among trading partners elsewhere in Asia raises the
possibility of mutually reinforcing weakness in the region as a
whole," warned Alfons Verplaetse, chairman of the Board of
Directors and president of BIS.
</P>
<P>
The sharp decline in commodity and oil prices will place a
heavy burden on a number of already fragile economies, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the buoyancy of stock markets and bond markets in
industrial countries, and the strength of capital flowing into
non-Asian emerging markets, could also be described as good news.
</P>
<P>
But Verplaetse pointed out that the enthusiasm for financial
markets also raises another specter: that it may not last, and
that the economic effects of a change might be difficult to
predict and to manage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
