<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Says Russia Passes Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 8 (Xinhua) -- President Boris Yeltsin said that
Russia has overcome the worst of its financial crisis, the
Itar-Tass news agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German magazine Der Spiegel, the
president said thanks to the measures taken by the Russian
government and to the outside backing, first of all from the seven
industrial countries, the peak of the crisis has basically pulled
down.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who will leave for Germany Monday on an official
visit, said foreign investors should have no reason for panic.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the present crisis was the crisis of a
financial system all over the world which Russia could not avoid.
</P>
<P>
The president also urged the government officials to exert more
efforts to improve the situation.
</P>
<P>
He stressed "political support" given to Russia from leaders of
the United States, Germany, France and Britain, noting that
"Russia was not begging for money any more since this period was
over for Russia."
</P>
<P>
At the end of last month, a serious financial crisis occurred in
the Russian market. Following a series of emergent measures
adopted by the government, the financial crisis started to relax.
</P>
</TEXT>
