<HEADLINE> Brisk Housing Sales In East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Shandong Province, an economic
powerhouse in east China, reported a 62 percent year-on-year
increase in residential housing sales in the first four months of
this year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 720,000 sq m of floor space were sold during the
period, with 640,000 sq m for home buyers.
</P>
<P>
The growing sentiment of buying houses has lifted the market
prices, bringing the average per sq m price to 1,245 yuan, 28
yuan more than that at the end of last year, according to Wang
Junmin, head of the provincial urban and rural construction
committee.
</P>
<P>
To cope with the increasing demand for housing, the provincial
government has increased investment in housing and real estates.
Statistics show that in the first four months, the provincial
government put two billion yuan in housing sector, up more than 70
percent from the year-ago period and accounting for 72 percent of
total real estate investment.
</P>
<P>
As some 7.08 million sq m of housing space is under
construction, Wang anticipated that the local housing market will
continue to be brisk this year.
</P>
<P>
A report from the provincial statistics bureau indicates that
in 1997, disposable annual income of people living at township and
above levels of the province averaged 5,191 yuan while their
per-capita living space posted at 9.5 sq.m.  
</P>
</TEXT>
