<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cases of Child Abuse Rise in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Stagnation of the economy and
poverty are to blame for rising cases of child abuse in Kenya, a
report by a local non-governmental organization says.
</P>
<P>
The report, quoted by the Daily Nation newspaper Monday,
estimates that Kenya has over 600,000 of the world's 100 million
abused children.
</P>
<P>
The report from the Coalition on Child Rights and Child
Protection in Kenya which brings together civil groups and
relevant governmental departments, further blames high inflation
rates and reduced family income for cruelty toward children.
</P>
<P>
The situation may worsen if the level of poverty among women
and children who form over 80 percent of Kenya's population which
reaches about 30 million, continues to rise, the report warns.
</P>
<P>
Although the Kenyan government has years ago pledged to reduce
household poverty by about 50 percent of the 1993 levels by 2000,
and reduce the severity of poverty by one-third, the battle has
not even started, says the report.
</P>
<P>
Nyanza, a densely populated province in western Kenya,
reported 4,400 cases of child abuse last year, compared with
3,001 cases in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The report lists sexual exploitation, child prostitution,
child labor, physical and mental torture, neglect and abandonment
as the rampant forms of abuse in Kenya today.
</P>
<P>
It says many children lack basic needs like health, nutrition,
education and sound environment and this has pushed the majority
into difficult circumstances.
</P>
<P>
The situation has further been exacerbated by the HIV/AIDS
scourge that has claimed more than 1.4 million lives in the east
African country, leaving children even more vulnerable, according
to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
