<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Wine Firm Targets Youth with New Drink </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- A new fruit wine, Tropical Kooler,
has entered the Kenyan market, but it will have to battle a
growing problem of competition from illegal imports, illicit brew
and high taxes.
</P>
<P>
The wine, which was recently launched by Kenya Wine Agencies
Ltd. (KWAL), is targeted at young and upcoming drinkers, and
comes in orange and strawberry flavors, media here reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
KWAL believes that the wine, which has a relatively low
alcohol content of eight percent, has no close competitors.
</P>
<P>
Paul Chemng'orem, KWAL's Managing Director, said that Kooler
was launched especially in response to consumers' demand for wine
with a low alcohol content.
</P>
<P>
KWAL, a leading importer and distributor of over 400
international and local brands, has been in the wine industry for
more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Although the firm relies heavily on foreign visitors for
sales, there are indications that an increasing number of middle
and upper income Kenyans now drink wine.
</P>
<P>
However, most liquor consumers in the east African country
prefer beer because it is cheaper.
</P>
<P>
Chemng'orem said Kenya has not developed a vibrant local wine
industry mainly due to the huge initial capital investment
required.
</P>
<P>
It launched its first locally manufactured wine, Papaya, in
1983, but now includes brands like Plum Rose, Milano, Kingfisher,
Celegration and Vin d'Ananas.
</P>
<P>
Papaya Dry Table Wine, the first locally manufactured grape
wine, began selling in September 1985, and won a silver medal for
quality in the prestigious Monte Selection contest in Lisbon,
Portugal in 1985. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
