<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Uncommitted to Israel's Pullback Idea: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States will not back
Israel with the commitment it seeks to the scope of the third
troop redeployment in the West Bank, a newspaper reported here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Haaretz daily quoted a senior U.S. official as saying that
despite the tremendous efforts exerted by the U.S. in forging an
agreement on the second redeployment, the Israelis and
Palestinians are still not on the verge of a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
For the last two weeks, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu has been assuring his Cabinet ministers that he is
awaiting the U.S. position on the third redeployment as the key to
an overall deal with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
A new dispute over the size of the third pullback seemed to
have prevent the sides from finalizing a deal on the second
redeployment, although Israel has reportedly accepted the
U.S. plan calling for a 13 percent withdrawal in the second
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is floating the idea of Israeli withdrawal from
another 2 percent before going into the final-status talks with
the Palestinians. The Palestinian side insisted on a sizable
third pullback and rejected the Netanyahu offer, saying such
percentage is too marginal to be accepted.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, therefore, apparently hoped that the U.S. would
commit itself to Israel on the third pullback by convincing the
Palestinians to endorse his idea.
</P>
<P>
But the unnamed U.S. official said Washington was noncommittal
on the third redeployment. "You can forget about a U.S. commitment
on the scope of a third pullback," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no way. The Hebron agreement took four and a half
months. Yet this second pullback issue has taken 15 months. At
this rate, there is no way we will even get to final status," he
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The official expressed frustration with the "painfully"
incremental style of negotiations exhibited by both Israelis and
Palestinian, where progress is measured in "inches."
</P>
<P>
Signally Washington's growing impatience, he said "I can not see
how we can continue throughout the summer."
</P>
<P>
"There is no way a mediator can substitute for the two sides
talking with each other," he said, "Unless the two sides deal with
each other, there is no way there can be progress on final
status."
</P>
<P>
Israeli Cabinet discussed the redeployment issue on Sunday,
but no decision was made.
</P>
<P>
Dampening the optimism over a possible quick breakthrough in
the long-running dispute over the second redeployment, Netanyahu
told the cabinet that there was still no agreement with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Nor was there an agreement with the U.S. on a broad outline for
the third redeployment, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
