<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Urges Peaceful Solution to Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem Monday called on all parties concerned to seek a peaceful
solution to the ethnic crisis in the Yugoslav province Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the Balkan foreign ministers'
meeting here, Cem said a peaceful settlement of the Kosovo issue
is of great significance to the peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of Albania, Bulgaria, Greece, Macedonia,
Romania, Turkey and the Yugoslav Federation attended the meeting
which centered on the Kosovo problem.
</P>
<P>
Officials of Russia, France, Italy, Germany, the United States
and Britain, which form the Contact Group for issues related to
the former Yugoslavia, as well as Croatia and Bosnia, took part in
the conference as observers.
</P>
<P>
"Any form of violence, excessive use of force and all forms of
terrorism have to be stopped immediately in Kosovo. It is my
government's sincere wish that talks for obtaining a durable and
effective solution to this problem start as soon as possible," Cem
said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the talks should seek ways of safeguarding the
human and civil rights of all inhabitants in Kosovo, including
ethnic Albanians, Serbs, Turks as well as others.
</P>
<P>
"The recent outflow of refugees has created a tragic situation
for the masses concerned and serious problems for neighboring
countries. We must solve the problem of Kosovo before it is too
late," Cem added.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Kosovo has been worsening since February when
the Serb police took tough measures against ethnic Albanians
seeking independence from the Yugoslav Federation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
