<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Cocoa Export Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria exported 52,583 tons of raw
cocoa beans in the first quarter of this year, an increase of 35
percent over the 34,037 tons in the same period of 1997, the
Business Concord said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report, quoting figures from the Federal Produce
Inspection Services, said that the development may have been a
result of lower processing activities in Nigeria's ailing cocoa
processing plants.
</P>
<P>
It is also seen as a sign of "good omen" for meeting the
International Cocoa Organization projection of 155,000 tons of
cocoa export for Nigeria by the close of the 1997/1998 harvest
season in May, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a report by the Guardian newspaper Monday said a
London-based company, Commco International Limited, has begun
discussion with the Cocoa Exporters Association of Nigeria (CEAN)
for investment in cocoa farms.
</P>
<P>
Pius Olaiya Ayodele, president of the Ondo State chapter of
the CEAN, was quoted as saying that the proposal aims to shoot up
Nigeria's annual cocoa production from the current 120,000 to
500,000 tons by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the Ondo chapter of the CEAN has begun
discussions with the state government for the lease of land for
cocoa plantation.
</P>
<P>
Cocoa was Nigeria's biggest foreign exchange earner until
earlier 1970s, when crude oil became Nigeria's number one export
product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
