<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria May Introduce Death Penalty for Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The head of the Nigerian National
Drug Law Enforcement Agency (NDLEA), Major-General Musa Bamaiyi,
has called for the reintroduction of death penalty to curb drug
trafficking in the West African country
</P>
<P>
Bamaiyi's call came just ahead of the special session on drugs
by United Nations General Assembly, which began in New York
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a workshop on "The drug problem and the Nigerian
media" at the weekend in Lagos, Bamaiyi said although his agency
has made progress in its fight against abuse and illicit traffic
of hard drugs, the phenomenon still posed great danger to the
populace.
</P>
<P>
He added that a serious disease requires a drastic, even
surgical remedy and that "capital punishment against drug
culprits was not too much in order to save thousands of
Nigerians and guide them to a useful existence."
</P>
<P>
Nigeria introduced death penalty for illicit traffickers in
dangerous drugs in 1985, under the administration of General
Mohammadu Buhari (1983-1985). Three persons were thus executed.
</P>
<P>
The death penalty was, however, abolished by the succeeding
government of General Ibrahim Babangida (1985-1993).
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Bamaiyi's suggestion may be
incorporated into the National Drug Control Master Plan,
developed by relevant government agencies non-governmental
organizations and professional interest groups.
</P>
<P>
The major components of the plan include adequacy and efficacy
of penal sanctions, demand reduction and control of illicit
supply, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
