<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strike Seen to Scare Investors in Philippine Airlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Airlines (PAL) said
Monday that the ongoing illegal strike by its more than 600 pilots
has scared interested foreign investors into breaking off talks
for a critical equity investment in the carrier.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, PAL said the four-day-old work stoppage by
the 625-strong pilots union, the Airline Pilots Association of the
Philippines (ALPAP), is dooming what may be the flag carrier's
final chance to stave off financial collapse.
</P>
<P>
PAL said it is losing between 150 million pesos (3.8 million
U.S. dollars) and 200 million pesos (5.1 million dollars) daily in
forfeited revenues, excluding incidental costs and expenses,
pushing the cash-strapped airlines closer to the brink of
insolvency.
</P>
<P>
Even before the strike took place, PAL said it was already
reeling from the worst financial crisis in its 57-year history, as
the Asian currency turmoil and the prolonged slump in the travel
market virtually choked off its cash flow.
</P>
<P>
In the last fiscal year ending March 1998, PAL suffered a net
loss of 8.1 billion pesos (206 million dollars), its largest ever.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to stay afloat, PAL had been engaged in serious
talks with a number of foreign carriers who were looking to take a
significant equity stake in the airlines.
</P>
<P>
But the work stoppage by ALPAP, in open defiance of two
government orders, has caused investors to lose interests in PAL,
the press release said.
</P>
<P>
ALPAP said earlier it was protesting the ordered retirement of
Captain Albino Collantes, 45, in December 1997 which PAL said was
its prerogative in line with an earlier collective bargaining
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The union said the pilot was too young to retire, and also
accused PAL management of cutting pilots rest hours and harassing
union members.
</P>
<P>
ALPAP and PAL have been locked in dispute over the forced
retirement of Collantes over which the Department of Labor and
Employment has assumed jurisdiction. The labor department also
issued two orders to prohibit the union from aggravating PAL's
financial woes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
