<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Says Eight Percent Growth Possible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The 8 percent economic growth the
Chinese government wants is possible if all people work together,
Chinese Vice Premier Wu Bangguo told a forum on the economic
situation in China last month, the full text of which was
published in today's "Economic Daily".
</P>
<P>
To do so requires an 11-percent increase in the country's
industrial added value output, based on the 1997's level, he said,
and this is a little bit difficult for all of 1998, based on
industrial production in the first quarter, but not impossible.
</P>
<P>
Wu, who is in charge of China's industrial production, said
that 59,000 state-owned enterprises lost 8.77 billion yuan in the
first quarter, but reported profits of 590 million yuan for the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Of 31 provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions in
China, only Heilongjiang, Yunnan, Guangdong, Fujian and Shandong
provinces and the municipality of Shanghai made profits from
January to March of this year, all of them supported by a group of
large local enterprises, while 12 other provinces lost more than
500 million yuan each during the same period.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the 14,000 large and medium-sized state-owned
enterprises went from earnings of 3.7 billion yuan in the first
quarter of 1997 to losses of 4.25 billion yuan in the first
quarter of this year, or 48.5 percent of the total losses incurred
by state industrial enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The State Council has had a wide range of measures like
increased investment, pushing consumer demand, and raising tax
rebates for a number of key exports, to ensure this year's
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Industrial production and economic efficiency will gradually
take a turn for the better in the last three quarters after these
measures are implemented, Wu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
