<HEADLINE> Share Prices Take Hammering on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Share prices took a hammering on
the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials
Index (STII) lost 39.89 points to close at 1,128.57 points Monday.
</P>
<P>
Traders said shares plunged as the falling yen forced Japanese
investors to dump shares and pulled down Southeast Asian
currencies.
</P>
<P>
"The market has been under strong sustained selling pressure
for a period of time. The currencies made it worse today and the
signs continue to look bad for the economy," a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The yen, which broke the 140 to the U.S. dollar barrier,
dragged the Singapore dollar and most regional currencies down,
pulling stocks down in their wake, they added.
</P>
<P>
Total market volume fell to 109.54 million units, valued at
207.34 million Singapore dollars (121.96 million U.S. dollars).
There were 38 rises against 272 falls while 281 other counters
remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Easyknit was the most actively traded stock as it registered a
turnover of 10.68 million units. It was followed by DBS Land which
had 8.58 million shares traded. IPC was next with 7.49 million
shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
NatBroad topped the gainers list of the day as it rose by 19.5
cents to finish at 1.00 U.S. dollar. Venture increased by 10 cents
to end at 4.44 Singapore dollars. New Toyo was up by 6 cents to
close at 0.34 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, CityDev W98 was the biggest loser as it
declined by 62 cents to end at 2.28 Singapore dollars. SIA F fell
by 55 cents to close at 8.35 Singapore dollars. F &AMP; N was down by
50 cents to finish at 4.70 Singapore dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
