<HEADLINE> Chinese And Foreign Scholars Discuss China's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and foreign specialists,
World Bank and Asian Development Bank executives, and Chinese
government officials met on Sunday in the city of Huangshan in
China's Anhui Province for a discussion of China's future and its
development.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held by China's State Development Planning
Commission, the World Bank, and the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
The participants, who include the futurist Alvin Toffler, are
discussing topics like economic development speed and structure,
environmental protection and ecological balance, financial reforms
and development, employment, and social security.
</P>
<P>
According to Hui Liangyu, Anhui's governor, who gave a
welcoming address yesterday, Anhui has had World Bank loans for 23
projects since 1982, worth 690 million U.S. dollars, and has
borrowed 397 million U.S. dollars worth of Asian Development Bank
loans to support four local projects.
</P>
<P>
There were 40 papers listed for presentation at the meeting,
which ends tomorrow. 
</P>
