<HEADLINE> S. Africa, France's N0.1 Trading Partner in Black </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 8 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has become
France's main trading partner in sub-Saharan Africa with trade
between the two countries almost doubling since 1994.
</P>
<P>
The sale of French products into South Africa was worth 4.7
billion Rand (about 940 million U.S. Dollars) last year, an
increase of 27 percent against the previous year, and French
market share for goods in South Africa rose four percent,
Business Day daily quoted a French Trade Commission report as
saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, exports from South Africa to France amounted to only
1.8 billion Rand (360 million U.S. Dollars). It is understood
that the trade deficit is an issue of concern for South Africa.
</P>
<P>
More than 125 French companies reportedly had a subsidiary in
South Africa, three times the number five years ago.
</P>
<P>
French investment in South Africa had become more diversified
and partnership had been formed with black business groups.
</P>
<P>
Besides, nine French banks are now situated in South Africa,
either as a subsidiary, a joint venture or as a representative
office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
