<HEADLINE> Zambia to Improve Health Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is expected
to spend over 40 million U.S. Dollars in upgrading 400 health
centers and renovating hospitals across the country, Zambia Daily
Maily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Ben Chirwa, spokesman of the Central
Board of Health, as saying here Sunday that 27 million Dollars
will be used to develop the health centers while remaining 13
million Dollars will be used to renovate hospitals.
</P>
<P>
He said some hospitals like that in Kitwe has already
submitted their project proposals, while Chilenje and Matero in
Lusaka are some of the medical centers that have benefited from
the program.
</P>
<P>
In three months the board will open the Chelston and Kamwala
medical centers, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said the health board will improve the conditions of
service for all its workers.
</P>
<P>
"We will give them better salaries, introduce rural
allowances, cater for housing and many more to encourage the
health workers operating in any area of Zambia," he said.
</P>
<P>
He made the speech after Hope Foundation founder, the first
lady Vera Chiluba, failed to distribute medical equipment and
drugs to Natukumo Clinic because there was neither infrastructure
nor medical personnel there.
</P>
<P>
This forced Ms Chiluba to fly back an assortment of drugs to
Mongu in Western Province where they were donated to Lewannika
General Hospital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
