<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Foreign Representative Offices in Vietnam Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The number of foreign offices in
Vietnam has dropped from the peak period of 1994-1997 when foreign
companies flocked to the country to establish their presence,
the Vietnam News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Many foreign representative offices have temporarily closed
down or reduced working staff. In the last five months, 30
offices have halted operations, bringing the total number of
shutdown offices to 295 nation-wide, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese trade officials attributed the drop to a saturation
of foreign companies and negative impacts from Asia's financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
According to vietnam's ministry of trade, of the 2,640
representative offices licensed to operate in Vietnam, 70 percent
are from the Asia-Pacific region, 23 percent from Europe and North
America and the rest from Southwest Asia and Africa, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Ho Chi Minh city, the country's business hub, has 1,750 foreign
representative offices with Japanese companies maintaining the
biggest presence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
