<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wellington Company Produces Drinking Water From Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- A Wellington company said it has
made a technological breakthrough in producing clear drinking
water out of thin air, The Evening Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Watermaster Technologies said the new process involves three
stages: the machine takes in air, extracts water from it and then
purifies it by passing it through an electrical filter and a
charcoal filter.
</P>
<P>
The electrical filter destroys any bacteria while the charcoal
filter removes solid materials.
</P>
<P>
The company said the technology used in Airwell 2000, the
machine as it has been named, has worldwide applications and can
alleviate drinking water shortages anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
It said worldwide patent searches have not found anything
similar apart from simple dehumidifiers. But most dehumidifiers
do not produce purified water.
</P>
<P>
Airwell 2000 can turn out 20 liters of clear drinking water a
day from the surrounding air. It can be used in areas where water
supply is poor or where there is pollution, the paper reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0176 </DOCNO>
