<HEADLINE>   Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
 leading French newspapers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The International Federation of Football (FIFA) will elect its
new president on Monday in Paris to succeed Joao Havelange. Because
of renegotiations of transmission rights with television companies
during the 1998 World Cup, FIFA has already earned 11 billion francs
(1.8 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
-- About 30 heads of state will meet from Monday in New York for
a week-long extraordinary session of the United Nations to
commemorate the 10th anniversary of the adoption of the
International Convention Against Illegal Trafficking of
Hallucinating and Psychotropic Drug. The conference will issue a
declaration to establish a new program to greatly reduce the number
of drug addicts -- around 190 million worldwide -- from now until
2008.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Despite the appeal by French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
for an end of the strike by pilots of Air France, no date is
fixed for a resumption of talks between the pilots and the
management. The management of Air France said all its
"capabilities to understand the pilots have dried up," while the
pilots expressed "total determination" to continue the conflict
until the end.
</P>
<P>
-- Four giants representing four continents will lead the
processions to be held on Tuesday afternoon to launch the World Cup.
The stectacle is designed by Jean-Pascal Levy Trumet and will be
backed by music composed by Hector Zazou. It will be completed at
the Concorde Square around the Egyptian Oblisk dressed up for the
occassion. 
</P>
