<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kaunda to Sue Zambian Govt for Wrongful Detention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Zambian former President and
opposition leader Kenneth Kaunda has instructed his lawyers to
sue the government for wrongful detention, Zambia's leading
independent newspaper, The Post, reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing cadres of his United National Independence Party
(UNIP) in Lusaka Saturday, Kaunda disclosed that he has asked his
lawyers to take the government to court because he had been
wrongly detained for five months for allegedly being involved in
last October's foiled military coup.
</P>
<P>
This followed a statement made last Thursday by Legal Affairs
Minister Vincent Malambo that the government has evidence against
Kaunda in the on-going treason trial although he was released by
the Lusaka High Court on June 1, which is widely believed to be a
deal brokered by South African President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Malambo said that the state entered a nolle prosequi against
Kaunda only because it found it inappropriate to continue with
the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda also indicated that he has no plans to retire from
party politics immediately saying he will only leave party
politics after making UNIP a very strong party which can remove
the ruling Movement for Muti-Party Democracy (MMD).
</P>
<P>
"Don't force me to reveal my secrets now. I will inform you of
my intentions at the (forthcoming) congress," said Kaunda.
</P>
<P>
However, the 74-year-old former president who ruled Zambia for
27 years after its independence in 1964 declared here last
Thursday that he is seriously considering the possibility to
resign from active party politics.
</P>
<P>
This declaration surprised the members of the country's
largest opposition party which has been bogged down in a severe
inter-fighting over the party leadership.
</P>
<P>
Some of them who do not want Kaunda to step down said that his
withdrawal will spell doom for UNIP and it may disband. They have
rejected his decision and agreed to petition him so that he can
change his mind.
</P>
<P>
While others including the party's national Chairman Malimba
Masheke, who has been allegedly collaborating with Secretary
General Sebastian Zulu to oust Kaunda, said that UNIP has capable
leaders to take over the party presidency after Kaunda's
retirement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
