<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Town Becomes Hub of E. African Cargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- As roads and railway networks in
east Africa collapse due to months of the heavy El Nino rains,
the western Kenyan town of Kisumu, bordering on Lake Victoria,
takes center stage in regional trade, handling ever more cargo.
</P>
<P>
Kisumu has become the hub of cargo transport in the region as
more and more traders route Tanzania and Uganda-bound shipments
through the third largest Kenyan city, the East African weekly
newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
A. R. Juma, an official of the Kenya Revenue Authority, was
quoted as saying that activity at the port has picked up
considerably over the past few months with ships from Uganda and
Tanzania queuing up for loading.
</P>
<P>
Long queues of wagons waiting to be loaded onto ships have
been evident in the past few weeks, with officials of the Kenya
Revenue Authority, Kenya Railways, Uganda Railways and Tanzania
Railway coordinating the activity jointly.
</P>
<P>
"It's the water hyacinth that slows down the operations of
this port (Kisumu), otherwise there is so much going on," Juma
added. The weed rampant on the world's second largest fresh water
lake causes long delays in loading and off-loading of cargo and
disrupts trades.
</P>
<P>
Wagons and containers piled up in Kenya's Indian Ocean port
Mombasa after two bridges in central Kenya were washed away on
May 16, forcing most Ugandan importers stopping transporting
goods by road.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Uganda Railways Corporation (URC) said the
corporation has increased the volume of Kampala-bound cargo going
through Kisumu.
</P>
<P>
"URC is using less of the Malaba line because it is more
expensive and slower than the Kisumu route," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said it took a ship one day to transport cargo to Kampala
from Kisumu, consuming 6,000 liters of fuel. A train would
consume 14,000 liters of fuel and take much longer.
</P>
<P>
While ships can carry up to 22 wagons one way, trains are
limited to eight wagons per trip, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian officials said that since the main railway line in
Tanzania was washed away by floods, importers from central and
western Tanzania have had to divert their cargo to Kisumu.
</P>
<P>
"The Dar-es-Salaam route is completely useless. The railway
line was washed away long ago and the roads are simply
impassable. Kisumu is the only direct route into Tanzania. It is
the fastest and the cheapest," said a navigator of a
Tanzania-bound ship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
