<HEADLINE> Zambian Citizens Urged to Boycott Illegal Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Health Minister Nkandu Luo
has urged the public to desist from obtaining medicines from
illegal dealers because they even do not understand the dosage
and often give wrong prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
Luo made the call here Sunday when she launched the pharmacy
awareness week, the theme of which is "poverty and equity access
to essential drugs", according to Zambia Daily Mail.
</P>
<P>
She reminded the Pharmaceutical Society of Zambia (PSZ) that
they have a task to fight street vending of medicines which has
become a danger to society.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted her as saying most of the dealers
who sell and prescribe the medicines do not understand how
dangerous some of the drugs are to human being.
</P>
<P>
Luo urged the public to obtain medication after appropriate
consultation with medical experts.
</P>
<P>
She said the government's policy is to provide Zambians with
access to cost effective and quality health care.
</P>
<P>
It is impressive to see a number of pharmacies opening up in
residential areas in most towns and this has improved the
accessibility of drugs, she said.
</P>
<P>
She called on PSZ to set up more pharmaceutical outlets in the
rural areas. 
</P>
