<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 08:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Officials Hold Surprise Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 8 (Xinhua) -- In a surprise move, Israeli
Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh and senior Palestinian negotiator
Saeb Erekat held talks on interim issues late Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported Monday that the meeting, held at the
official residence of U.S. Ambassador to Israel Edward Walker,
focused on the interim issues, including the seaport, Dahaniya
airport, and industrial zones in Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The last time these issues were discussed was two months ago.
</P>
<P>
The radio said the Americans initiated the meeting in the hope
of launching the projects once an agreement on the second Israeli
redeployment in the West Bank is achieved.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's unexpected meeting was held amid growing speculation
that Israel and the Palestinian side are close to reaching an
agreement on the second redeployment based on a U.S. proposal.
</P>
<P>
Local Hebrew daily Haaretz disclosed last week that the latest
draft of the U.S. proposal demands that the outstanding interim
issues be implemented within 12 weeks, during which the second
redeployment would be carried out.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio also quoted unconfirmed reports as saying that
Israel recently held talks with European Union (EU) officials and
agreed to give the Palestinians a seaport and a working airport.
</P>
<P>
This was part of an understanding to prevent the imposition of
EU sanctions on products originated from Jewish settlements in the
occupied territories. Israel and the EU waged a war of words last
month over EU's threat to boycott settlement products.
</P>
<P>
Despite the newly emerging optimism that an Israeli decision on
the second redeployment is nearer, Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu denied Sunday at the weekly Cabinet meeting that Israel
was on the verge of reaching an agreement with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He said contacts with Washington were continuing and focusing
on the third redeployment.
</P>
<P>
It appeared that Israel has accepted in principle the U.S. plan
calling for a 13 percent withdrawal in the second redeployment.
However, a new dispute over the size of the third pullback
prevented the sides from fixing an agreement.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is reportedly floating the idea of a 2 percent
pullback in the third redeployment, which has been rejected flatly
by the Palestinian side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
