<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 08:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE, Oman, Qatar Ready to Help Raise Oil Prices: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Oil Minister Ali Bin
Ibrahim Al-Naimi has indicated that the United Arab Emirates
(UAE), Oman and Qatar are ready to help enhance oil prices, the
Saudi Press Agency reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Upon returning home late Sunday from a one-day visit to the
three countries, Al-Naimi said that his counterparts expressed
their countries' readiness to seek ways of stabilizing the world
oil market, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The four oil exporting countries, alongside Kuwait and Bahrain,
comprise the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC), a regional political
and economic alliance. The six economies are heavily reliant on
oil revenues.
</P>
<P>
Al-Naimi said that after consultations, positive results will
soon be seen. But he did not say whether the three countries have
agreed to cut their oil output.
</P>
<P>
He said that he briefed his counterparts on the talks in
Amsterdam, the Netherlands, last Thursday held between him and
oil ministers of Venezuela and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico agreed during the talks to
cut their oil output by a further 450,000 barrels per day as of
July 1.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi official said that most oil producing countries,
including the GCC member states, are striving to shore up the oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
The world oil prices had slumped due to weak demand in
Southeast Asian countries hit by financial turmoil and Iraq's
return to the oil market. The benchmark Brent Crude is traded at
around 14 U.S. dollars a barrel, five dollars lower than the
average price last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
