<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia, Yemen Agree to Continue Border Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia and Yemen have
agreed that their joint technical and legal border committee
continue meetings for the final demarcation of their boundary, the
Saudi Press Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made Sunday when Saudi Prince and Defense
Minister Sultan Bin Abdul-Aziz met visiting Yemeni Minister of
Legal Affairs Abdullah Ahmed Ghanim and Minister of Justice Ismail
Ahmed Al-Wazeer in Saudi port city of Jeddah, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi leader said that his country hoped talks would
continue to solve the border dispute "cordially."
</P>
<P>
The Yemeni delegation arrived in Saudi Arabia a week ago on an
unannounced visit.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have been locked in border disputes since
1934. The tension eased after the signing of a Memorandum of
Understanding in 1995 concerning the solution of the border issues
and bilateral ties are improving.
</P>
<P>
Border demarcation negotiations have since been conducted
through the joint committee.
</P>
<P>
Yemeni Prime Minister Abdul-Karim Al-Aryani has voiced his
keenness to finalize the border demarcation after he took office
in May.
</P>
<P>
Yemeni government has also expressed willingness to continue
efforts to reach a just and acceptable settlement of the border
issue to "ensure security and stability in the area, strengthen
bilateral ties as well as foster social and economic relations
between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
The two countries held their last round of talks in May when
Saudi Interior Minister Naif Bin Abdel Aziz sent a letter to his
Yemeni counterpart Hussain Moh'd Arab shortly after Yemeni new
cabinet was formed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
