<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Trying To Clean Up Suzhou River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai wants to step up cleaning
up the main river in the city this year, the 120-km-long Suzhou,
to make it clean again by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Xu Kuangdi says that this has long been the wish of the
city's 13 million people, and it is expected to become one of the
city's sightseeing spots, instead of of mainly a shipping channel.
</P>
<P>
The river had an abundance of fish in the last century, back
when fishing by the riverbank was one of the ten major scenes in
Shanghai, but the river became seriously polluted as the city
developed its economy.
</P>
<P>
By the latter part of the 1980s, Shanghai began the first stage
of its Pollution Control Project and stopped 1.4 million tons of
polluted water daily.
</P>
<P>
This made a visible change but failed to change the water
quality of the river enough, because of the number of pollution
sources. So, last year, Shanghai set up a special office in charge
of river treatment, with Mayor Xu in charge, and a special
enforcement team, which has dealt with 300 tons of rubbish
floating on the river.
</P>
<P>
This giant Comprehensive Harnessing Project, which runs into
the next century, will cost 20 billion yuan, and has received
1.3 million yuan in donations from China and abroad.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
