<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Not to Reduce Scale of Land Sales: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Robert Pope, director of lands of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), said here
Monday that the government will not reduce the scale of land sales
in spite of the current fluctuating property market.
</P>
<P>
After addressing the Guangdong-Hong Kong Valuation Seminar
1998, which is being held at the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center, Pope told reporters that in the first two
months of this fiscal year the land disposed by the government has
been sold at reasonable prices.
</P>
<P>
There is no need to worry that this year's income of land sales
will be lower than expected, Pope said.
</P>
<P>
He said that although some developers find it difficult to
raise funds due to the fluctuating property market, the government
has raised 10 billion HK dollars (1.15 billion U.S. dollars)
through land transactions in the first two months of this fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
"The property market has been fluctuating but all my land sales
have gone on schedule," Pope said.
</P>
<P>
The government will watch closely the impact of the property
market to the overall economy of Hong Kong, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Lands Department is responsible for the disposal and
management of all government land and the acquisition of land for
public projects in the SAR.
</P>
<P>
The department raised 72 billion HK dollars (9.23 billion
U.S. dollars) last year and it expects to raise some 60 billion HK
dollars (7.69 billion U.S. dollars) this year, Pope said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
