<HEADLINE> Desertification Warnings In Northern and Northwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 8 (Xinhua) -- China's State Forestry
Administration has emphasized the need to control desertification
in northern and northwestern parts of the country by planting
grass and trees to reduce the effect of sandstorms.
</P>
<P>
Two strong sandstorms have hit the area since April, mainly in
areas with fewer trees and grass.
</P>
<P>
China suffers from serious desertification problems on 2.6
million square kilometers of land or 27.3 percent of its total
area. Annual losses from desertification are figured at 54 billion
yuan (6.5 billion US dollars), and desert areas are growing by
2,460 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Forestry specialists attribute the growth to man and to climate
changes, and say that population increases in these areas have put
pressure on land with grazing in pasture regions and deterioration
of grassland. In the Loess Plateau, planting on hillsides has
turned a large amount of arable land sandy.
</P>
<P>
Specialists point out that the delayed control of
desertification is a result of lack of investment, and although
the country has designated 21 counties for desert control, they
have only 400,000 yuan each for the sand control project.
</P>
<P>
They suggest that the state increase spending on desert control
in combination with agricultural development and poverty relief
projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newspaper Clipping New Business in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Newspaper clipping service is now
a new business vogue in Shanghai, providing information in an
often neglected way.
</P>
<P>
Yi Yueming, head of one of 10 companies engaged in the service,
explains, "What we do is to clip out useful information from
newspapers before throwing them into trash cans, and offer them
to clients after classification."
</P>
<P>
Yi started the service two years ago and now subscribes to more
than 200 newspapers. His company clips out all kinds of articles
for dozens of clients.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1990s, the Shanghai Library opened the first
service of this kind, providing articles on various subjects like
finance, securities, real estate, and law for many big
enterprises, who are now its long-term customers.
</P>
<P>
Because of the wide range of information provided at low cost,
the service is being used by more companies, and some clipping
companies now offer in-depth market analyses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
