<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Armed Burundi Refugees Harassing Tanzanians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 8 (Xinhua) -- More than 450 Tanzanians
living in Biharamulo-West District, Kagera Region, have fled
their home over the past two months after being harassed by armed
Burundi refugees.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by the Member of Parliament for
Biharamulo-West, Anatoli Choya, who said that the refugees have
been terrorizing local residents, especially by robbing their
property.
</P>
<P>
"Many of our people have lost their property and fled their
houses for fear of being killed by armed Burundi refugees who
most of the time plunder whatever valuable belongings they find,"
The Guardian Monday quoted Choya as saying.
</P>
<P>
Choya told the paper in Morogoro over the weekend that local
authorities have been unable to control the bandits who come from
Msuhura refugee camp in the Ngara District on the border with
Burundi.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a joke that some of our fellow Tanzanians have fled
their houses and have become refugees in their own country," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The MP said that the district will most probably face an acute
shortage of food this year as some 50 Tanzanian households have
abandoned farms for fear of being attacked.
</P>
<P>
Choya said that it is difficult to seize the bandits because
they hid themselves very well.
</P>
<P>
Those who fled their houses are currently accommodated at a
police station nearby and a house belonging to a Norwegian-aided
project, Choya said.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania plays host to around 225,000 mainly Hutu refugees who
fled Burundi's civil war, according to the United Nations High
Commissioner of Refugees (UNHCR). 
</P>
</TEXT>
