<HEADLINE> Forests for Sandy Higher Areas of China's Qaidam Basin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Some early success in an unirrigated
afforestation research project for sandy areas has given some hope
for desert control workers in the Qaidam Basin in China's Qinghai
Province.
</P>
<P>
The basin has an average elevation of 3,200 meters and is rich
in salt, oil, and natural gas, but its elevation and dry climate
have meant sparse vegetation and serious desertification and made
it difficult to get access to these resources.
</P>
<P>
So, local forestry personnel began a 3.73-million-yuan pilot
project in 1995 to improve sandy areas, and have added nearly 250
hectares of forests in the form of 187 forest belts, and brought
more than 330 ha of sandy areas under control.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have also started a 156-ha experimental center using
unirrigated and deep-sowing methods that has resulted in a forest
survival rate of more than 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
The dry afforestation technique will make large-scale
improvement projects possible, they say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Sets up Marine Data Center in E. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- An oceanographic database center
providing marine data and maps has started operating at Kenya's
Indian Ocean port city of Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
The center, based at the Kenya Marine and Fisheries Research
Institute, will provide scientific information also useful to
conservationists, the East African weekly newspaper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The center will serve Tanzania, Comoros, Madagascar,
Seychelles, Mauritius, Reunion, Mozambique and Somalia, said the
report. The eight states adopted the eastern Africa action plan
on the establishment of an oceanographic center in 1985.
</P>
<P>
The plan was to enhance sustainable development and management
of the marine environment and resources in the region.
</P>
<P>
The database, known as geographical information system (GIS),
covers climate, hydrology, oceanography and coastal types and
contains details on marine flora and fauna, and on fishing.
</P>
<P>
"There is an urgent need to develop data centers in the region
which can ensure that (information) is collected in standard
formats, is quality controlled and archived," said Ezekiel Okemw,
the regional coordinator of Mombasa Oceanographic Center.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. statistics, up to 1996 none of the countries
in eastern Africa had set up a national oceanographic data
center.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania had a designated nationals agency for ocean data
management, established in 1971, but it was moribund.
</P>
<P>
However, several countries in the region have now initiated
national databases, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
