<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Leaves For Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
leaves here Monday afternoon for Germany to attend Russian-German
summit consultations.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl are expected to
discuss issues ranging from financial markets and German
investment in Russia to bilateral cooperation in the mining and
space industries.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's entourage includes Deputy Prime Minister Oleg
Sysuyev, Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov, Economics Minister
Yakov Urinson, Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev, Interior Minister
Sergei Stepashin, Finance Minister Mikhail Azdornov and Atomic
Energy Minister Yevgeny Adamov.
</P>
<P>
The ministers are scheduled to hold parallel meetings with
their German counterparts Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
"They will have enough work for a whole night," Itar-Tass news
agency quoted Yeltsin as saying.
</P>
<P>
Germany is Russia's largest trading partner. Bilateral trade
last year amounted to 32 billion German marks (about 17.7 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, Moscow is dissatisfied with the trade structure which
features export of Russian raw materials and import of German
finished goods.
</P>
<P>
Russia is urging Germany to increase investment in
Russia. German investments, mainly in the services and trade
sectors, now account for some 11 percent of total foreign
investment in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin will have a working breakfast with Gerhard Schroder,
speaker of Germany's upper house of parliament, Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is seen by observers as of special importance
because Schroder might become the next German chancellor.
</P>
<P>
Schroder has been nominated as the candidate for chancellor of
the Social Democratic Party, which is leading opinion polls in the
run-up to the September elections.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin is scheduled to return to Moscow Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
