<HEADLINE> 600,000 Zimbabweans Need Food Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Over 600,000 people in Zimbabwe's
south-eastern drought-stricken area need urgent food relief, The
Herald daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the government has ferried over 600 tons of maize
to the area. However, food delivery is expected to last only
until the end of this month when more rail wagons are expected to
bring in grain.
</P>
<P>
"We have managed to transport 12,000 bags of maize using rail
to Chriedzi district. This has improved food deliveries in the
district but the problem is far from being over.
</P>
<P>
"The government is facing a critical shortage of trucks for
the transportation of grain and the problem is being worsened by
the long distances," Masvingo Provincial Administrator Alphonse
Chikurira said in an interview Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to ensure that every family which has
registered gets food. One major problem we are still faced with
is where to relocate cattle to," said Chikurira.
</P>
<P>
Villagers have driven all their cattle to the banks of the
Runde river in search of grazing.
</P>
<P>
This has resulted in serious pressure on the land, threatening
the area with massive land degradation and siltation of the
river. The area was hit by the third consecutive drought. 
</P>
</TEXT>
