<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition to Stage "Long March" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's seven-party opposition
alliance will stage a two-day "long march" to the country's
southeastern Chittagong Hill Tracts beginning Tuesday to protest
against the peace treaty the government signed with the region's
tribals last December.
</P>
<P>
The major opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) would
start the march at 7 a.m. and stop at the seaport city of
Chittagong in the evening before restarting there Wednesday
morning towards Khagrachhari, one of the three hill districts, a
press release reaching here Monday said.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference Sunday, BNP Chairperson and leader of the
Opposition in Parliament Khaleda Zia said that if her party
returned to power, it would amend the "unconstitutional"
provisions in the accord.
</P>
<P>
"We also favor peace accord...but the one signed (between the
government and the tribals) contains some unconstitutional
provisions which require amendment," she said.
</P>
<P>
While the BNP alleged that the government was obstructing
preparations for the "long march", Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina
pledged Monday that her government would not obstruct the "long
march," as "we believe in democracy."
</P>
<P>
The opposition has fiercely attacked the treaty since it was
signed in December 1997, accusing it of "violating the
Constitution" and "ignoring the interest of the nation."
</P>
<P>
The seven-party alliance includes the BNP, the Jammat-e-Islami,
the Jatiya Party, the Democratic League, the National Democratic
Party, the Progressive Nationalist Party and the Democratic
Nationalist Alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
