<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Cozy Nest for the Old in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 8 (Xinhua) -- It's a rainy morning in Kowloon,
Hong Kong. The melodies of "Glory, Glory, Alleluia!" played by an
organ and a violin are heard from the entrance of a hillside
apartment building.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-one-year-old T.W. Chan and his friend are enjoying the
duet they played, once and again, in the first-floor lounge at the
beginning of a new day in their comfort lives after retirement.
</P>
<P>
Nearby, some others are reading newspapers and magazines,
watching TV, chatting with each other or simply relaxing in the
sofa, in an atmosphere of neighborhood harmony.
</P>
<P>
This scene is pretty usual in the first-ever house for senior
citizens prepared by the government of Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
The seven-story, 197-room apartment building was built
specially for the old people who can hardly afford the housing
expenses after retirement. Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
officiated the opening of the apartment on May 9.
</P>
<P>
Over 150 residents have moved in since January 16, 1998. Most
of them, aged between 60 and 83, are living alone and all on their
own.
</P>
<P>
With transparent roofs, the lodgers can enjoy the sunshine
without walking out of the building. Looking out from the
balconies is the scenic hills of Lam Tin, Kowloon. Right adjacent
to the well-equipped building is a shop of the city's largest
department store, Wellcome.
</P>
<P>
Along the walkways which circle the rooms on each floor are
clean and tidy public sitting and dining areas and laundry rooms,
as well as private kitchens and bathrooms allocated to each
resident. There are also activity rooms where some paintings of
the residents are displayed.
</P>
<P>
It is very cheap to rent such apartments, said Mr. Chan, who
used to be a teacher. It costs some 730 HK dollars (about 94
U.S. dollars) a month to rent a room here, about one-third of
renting a similar apartment in ordinary apartment buildings.
</P>
<P>
In Mr. Chan's room, there is a double-deck bed, a desk, an
organ, a stereo and a television set. Almost all corners of the
music lover's room are filled with books and cassette tapes.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Chow Min and Ms. Chan Siu Fong, two of the three welfare
assistants working in the apartment, said they feel happy to work
here.
</P>
<P>
The welfare assistants sometimes organize activities to welcome
new comers or entertain the lodgers. An old lady said the
assistants "are warm-hearted and treat us very well."
</P>
<P>
From time to time, some volunteer workers join the welfare
assistants to help the old people.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Chow said the HKSAR government has planned to open over
3,000 such apartment rooms for the old people in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
