<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax Income From Macao Casinos Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Tax income from Macao casinos rose 22
percent in 1997 over the previous year mainly due to a tax rate
increase, the Macao Daily News reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Macao casinos handed over some six billion patacas (about 750
million U.S. dollars) of tax last year, up 22 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
The increase was mainly because of the rise in tax rate from 30
percent of gross income to 31.8 percent. The increase was decided
in mid-1996.
</P>
<P>
The share of casino tax income has played an increasing role in
the government's revenue as Macao has been hit by an economic
slow-down since 1993.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Macao Tourism and Amusement Company (STDM),
which monopolizes all casinos in Macao, launched Asia's first
football lottery on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Stanley Ho, managing director of STDM, said last Friday at a
launching ceremony that he expected a turnover of up to one
billion patacas (about 125 million U.S. dollars) during the
upcoming 98' World Cup in France alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
