<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers to Pave Way for E. African Assembly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- A committee of legislators from
the national assemblies of Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania is to be
formed in preparation for the establishment of an East African
Legislative Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken at a two-day meeting attended by the
speakers of the three assemblies in Arusha, a northern Tanzanian
town where the East African Cooperation (EAC) Secretariat is
based, the East African weekly reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 19 lawmakers have agreed that the composition of the
committee should be determined by the speakers taking into
consideration the different parliamentary interest groups in
their countries.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed the composition, functions, powers and
privileges, proceedings and budget of the proposed assembly, as
well as the proposed draft treaty which should be approved by the
presidents of the three states in November.
</P>
<P>
For effective representation, they said, the proposed assembly
should have 45 members who appoint the Speaker, Clerk and other
officers.
</P>
<P>
The meeting proposed that each country choose 15 lawmakers,
which should reflect the composition of each national parliament,
including gender and other special interest groups.
</P>
<P>
The assembly will be able to discuss any matters pertaining to
EAC and liaise with the national legislatures on matters
affecting the regional community.
</P>
<P>
The would-be candidate should not be a minister or head of
department in any of the three countries. They should also not be
employees of the EAC or the East African Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
It was agreed that the person elected Speaker of the East
African Assembly should cease to be a member of parliament in his
own country and should serve in office for five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
