<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Meeting Overshadowed by Ethiopia-Eritrea Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 8 (Xinhua) -- African ministers ended a
four-day meeting here Sunday night to set stage for their heads of
state and government to plan the future of the world's poorest
continent at a summit.
</P>
<P>
But with escalation of armed conflict between Ethiopia and
Eritrea, the Council of Ministers of the Organization of African
Unity (OAU) had to call two special sessions to take care of the
hot issue.
</P>
<P>
Along with the reported escalating armed conflict at the Horn
of Africa, the two countries staged heated diplomatic wars at the
international conference center here.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of both countries called emergency press
conferences even when the ministerial meeting was underway.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia charged that Eritrean fighter planes bombed its
northern border town of Mekelle Friday and Saturday, killing more
than 40 civilians, including school children, and wounding about
150.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea denied the accusation, claiming that the airport in
the southern outskirts of its capital Asmara was bombed and one of
Ethiopian planes on the bombing mission was gunned down, with the
pilot captured.
</P>
<P>
To handle the situation, the ministerial meeting adopted a
resolution at midnight Friday, urging the two to end all
hostilities "at the same time and simultaneously."
</P>
<P>
But it has proved to be of little use when bombing and killing
resumed Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
It is mostly because of the worsening situation that the
meeting was extended by a whole day to close down only on Sunday
night so as to have more time to consider the issue, among other
things.
</P>
<P>
Despite the interruptions caused by the escalating conflict,
the Council of Ministers has basically fulfilled its targets set
for its 68th Ordinary Session.
</P>
<P>
After careful consideration, the councillors adopted in the
past four days more than 30 resolutions, which highlight what
African countries would plan to do to promote peace and economic
development.
</P>
<P>
All the resolutions will be submitted to the three-day 34th OAU
summit, scheduled to open on Monday, for further deliberation.
</P>
<P>
The coming summit is expected to give due attention to the
Ethiopia-Eritrea conflict, a critical issue whose solution would
have important bearing on peace and stability in Africa at a time
when progress has been made in the settlement of crises in
Liberia, Sierra Leone and other parts of Africa.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, how to establish a continental peacekeeping
force is expected to become one of the major points for discussion
at the summit.
</P>
<P>
Economic issues will also be a major topic at the summit as
encouraging growth has appeared in the continent in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
After being mired in almost two decades of economic crises,
Africa has obtained considerable progress, with the growth
rate up from one percent in 1990 to five percent last year.
</P>
<P>
The outlook is so optimistic that observers say that
Africa is potentially at the point of a takeoff.
</P>
<P>
To maintain the momentum in development, however,
there are a lot of problems for Africa to deal with.
</P>
<P>
Beside enjoying peace and stability, African countries have to
follow suitable economic policies and reduce their heavy debt
burden.
</P>
<P>
While trying to enhance the effectiveness of the Central Organ
of the Mechanism for Conflict Prevention, Management and
Resolution, OAU members also have to ensure a sound
performance of the African Economic Community (AEC), established
last year for continental economic integration.
</P>
<P>
Social problems, including food supply, child labor, refugees,
returnees and displaced persons and education, should also be duly
coped with.
</P>
<P>
Now that resolutions on these issues have been adopted at the
Council of Ministers meeting, the next thing is for African
leaders to make final decisions to realize their political will
and bring into the the new millennium an Africa of peace, unity,
democracy and development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0238 </DOCNO>
