<HEADLINE> Demand For Domestic Workers on Rise in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The demand for domestic helpers
paid on an hourly base is on the rise in major Chinese cities, a
survey by an information company under the State Statistics Bureau
indicated.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that over two million families in Beijing,
Shanghai, Guangzhou, Chengdu, Xi'an, Shenyang, and Qingdao--the
seven cities surveyed, have hired the hourly-paid domestic workers,
accounting for 24.7 percent of the total households.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that neighborhood service offices in the
seven cities now can provide the hourly-paid jobs to about 600,000
people, and that about 350,000 more hands are still needed to
cater to growing need.
</P>
<P>
The service is popular because, compared with the full-time
domestic workers, the hourly paid workers can provide flexible
services according to the need of their employers while do not
need their employers to provide accommodation, the survey
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
