<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Issue Domestic Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BANGKOK, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The first lot of Thailand's 500
billion baht (11.9 billion U.S. dollars) domestic bonds will be
issued by the end of this month, inaugurating the restructuring of
liabilities of the Financial Institutions Development Fund (FIDF).
</P>
<P>
The first lot of 50 billion baht (1.19 billion dollars) bond
issue will have a maturity of one year, and will be placed with
local and overseas financial institutions, the Bangkok Post Monday
quoted Deputy Finance Minister Pisit Leeahtam as saying.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister said that the bonds will be issued by the
Finance Ministry for sale to the FIDF, which will then resell the
instruments into the market.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry will be the issuer of the bonds in order
to restructure the FIDF's debt from short-term to long-term.
</P>
<P>
The government estimates that FIDF has run up losses of 500
billion baht (11.9 billion dollars) from its support of ailing
banks and finance companies over the past year.
</P>
<P>
An executive decree passed last month authorizes the issue of
up to 500 billion baht worth of domestic bonds to restructure
short-term liabilities of FIDF into long-term obligations, saving
costs on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Pisit said funds raised from the bond sale will be used by
FIDF to repay maturing short-term debts.
</P>
<P>
The first lot of the bonds was designed to test the market and
allow the authorities to choose a one-year maturity to avoid
excessive costs for the government.
</P>
<P>
Pisit said once the market stabilizes, the ministry will issue
long-term bonds of five, ten or 20 years.
</P>
<P>
He refused to tell the exact rates of the bonds, but said that
with liquidity tight, the ministry is likely to accept high
interest rates for the first lot. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0251 </DOCNO>
