<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Council of Ministers Session Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The 68th Ordinary Session of
the Council of Ministers of the Organization of African Unity
(OAU) ended here midnight Sunday after a one-day delay.
</P>
<P>
Delegations from the 53 OAU member states adopted more than 30
resolutions which highlight what the African countries plan to do
to promote peace and economic development in the world's poorest
continent.
</P>
<P>
All the resolutions will be submitted to a three-day OAU
summit, scheduled to open Monday morning, for further deliberation.
</P>
<P>
One resolution, which becomes the focus of attention at the
International Conference Center here, came out of a special
session called on Friday night, urging for an immediate end to all
hostilities between Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The special session was held after reports of mutual air
attacks between the two countries Friday morning, when Ethiopia
accused Eritrea of wounding five civilians.
</P>
<P>
A number of resolutions adopted by the Council of Ministers
meeting touched on political crises in Rwanda, Somalia, Angola,
the Comoros and Burundi after the delivery of reports on the
issues by OAU Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim.
</P>
<P>
Delegates agreed to enhance the effectiveness of the Central
Organ of the Mechanism for Conflict Prevention, Management and
Resolution in a bid to bring lasting peace to the entire continent.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also discussed the financial situation and
structural reform of the 53-member continental organization, while
appealing for international assistance to the national re-building
of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
As at the previous sessions, the Council of Ministers also
adopted resolutions in support of Palestine and Libya, calling for
an early solution to the crises they face with Israel and Britain
and the United States respectively.
</P>
<P>
Food supply, child labor, refugees, returnees and displaced
persons, education, human rights and other social problems were
among issues discussed at the four-day session, chaired by Burkina
Faso Foreign Minister Ablasse Ouedraogo.
</P>
<P>
Ouedraogo, replacing Executive Chairman Jakaya Kikwete,
Tanzanian foreign minister, will remain in office for two
consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
According to reliable sources, the delegates also had heated
discussions over Africa's seats in the anticipated expanded United
Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
On the economic front, the Council of Ministers has decided to
submit its draft resolution on the charter of the African Economic
Community to the 34th summit for the heads of state and government
to finalize.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, however, could not spend much time on economic
issues because of the conflict between Ethiopia and Eritrea, OAU
Spokesman Pascal Gayana told reporters at a news briefing after
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
But the heads of state and government will make it up at the
coming summit, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
