<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Skoda Reports Sharp Drop in Sales in Five Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Czech Republic's major car maker
Skoda said Sunday that its domestic sales in the first five months
this year registered a sharp drop of 15.1 percent to 35,000 units.
</P>
<P>
That the company would find no way to realize its sales goal
this year is a foregone conclusion, according to a senior Skoda
sales manager.
</P>
<P>
The manager attributed the decreased sales to the country's
recent unstable political situation and economic depression,
which, he said had resulted in Czech people's lower income in real
terms and weaker purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
Facing serious situation in the home market, Skoda is trying
its best to explore overseas market.
</P>
<P>
It plans to increase by more than 30 percent its export to
Germany, Italy and Austria within the following six months.
</P>
<P>
It also sees a bright prospect in the Chinese market and plans
to resume its suspended car trade with China.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Skoda lived a golden time with a record output of
357,000 units, up 35.9 percent from the previous year, and sales
also increased by 28.8 percent to 336,000 units. 
</P>
</TEXT>
