<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Western Chinese Battle Desert Invasion (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The canal is only one of a number of water conservation
projects here, the largest of which is in a canyon in the Kunlun
Mountains.
</P>
<P>
The 1.4-billion-yuan (168 million US dollars) construction
project is part of the Ninth Five-Year-Plan (1995-2000). When it
is completed in three years, it will be able to irrigate a
20,000-hectare area.
</P>
<P>
"A cubic meter of water from this expensive project will cost
three yuan, a very high price, but we are more concerned with what
the social returns the project will bring to this area," says Wang
Shijiang, who is in charge of the project.
</P>
<P>
Wang says that the central government is providing most of the
money for this important poverty-relief project, with water
conservation being the key to fighting desertification and getting
rid of poverty.
</P>
<P>
The increased amount of water has already helped the oasis grow
24,666 hectares in the past three years, 14,666 hectares of that
in farmland.
</P>
<P>
Water also allowed 100,000 hectares of trees to be planted in
woods, along roads, and in courtyards. The central and regional
governments are setting aside 400 million yuan annually for other
developments in Hotan.
</P>
<P>
The "three-dimentional agriculture" is one of these,
emphasizing the link between grains, vegetables, and fruits to
save farmland and make the oasis beautiful.
</P>
<P>
A local winery purchases grapes, pomegranates, and roses from
farmers to produce fruity wines, which are sold in other parts of
China, thanks to the Tarim Railway that crosses the desert.
</P>
<P>
Local officials are also placing hopes on oil exploration, from
the heart of the desert to the Kunlun Mountains, and one well
drilled last autumn shows great oil and gas potential.
</P>
<P>
In the view of Chinese economists, the Hotan oasis is a land
full of hope, and they say that the thousand-year-old silk
industry, the new gardening, the winery, and the oil potential
provide strong support for local people in their struggle against
the desert. 
</P>
</TEXT>
