<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Adopts New Measures to Curb Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The government of Guangzhou,
capital of south China's Guangdong Province, will strictly curb
the exhaust of motor-bikes and prohibit the use of plastic bags, a
leading official for environmental protection in the city said
today.
</P>
<P>
The authorities will force the installation of exhaust
purifiers on 400,000 motor-bikes, urge residents and shopping
malls to use paper bags instead of plastic ones and expand the
network for supplying liquefied natural gas to shops and
residences, said Gan Haizhang, head of the local environmental
protection bureau.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the bureau will release daily air quality reports
to the public beginning this month, said Gan.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the city government adopted regulations on reducing
pollution from motor vehicles and plastic bags. The amount of lead
in the air declined by 61 percent in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
After the beginning of the ban on horns on motor vehicles, the
noise index in old districts such as Yuexiu, Liwan, Dongshan and
Haizhu decreased greatly, Gan said.
</P>
<P>
The city also called on the general public to care more about
the environment they live in through reporting the daily air
quality. Guangzhou issued weekly air-quality reports last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
