<HEADLINE> Thai Defense Ministry Troubled by Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BANGKOK, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Foreign debts have become a major
headache for the Defense Ministry of Thailand, which has already
been hard-pressed by budget cuts over the past year, the Bangkok
Post said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry now has 5 billion baht (119 million U.S.
dollars) in foreign debts which mature this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
It still has no idea how to pay these debts, since the
ministry has already had its budget cut back to the bone, the
newspaper quoted a ministry official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The armed forces received a budget of 75 billion baht (1.79
billion dollars) in fiscal 1998, forcing expenditure cuts of up to
16 billion baht (380 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Cuts for the Defense Ministry have been particularly harsh, as
the government has directed scarce funds to key investments to
build a social safety net and develop the country's industrial
base.
</P>
<P>
However, the government has set aside 2 billion baht (47.6
million dollars) to help deal with increased state debt stemming
from the depreciation of the baht. About half is expected to be
used for the Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The maturing foreign debt is actually about 15 billion baht
(357 million dollars), but 10 billion baht (238 million dollar)
has been successfully rolled over, leaving 5 billion baht (119
million dollars) of obligations due by September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
