<HEADLINE> U.S. Used Nerve Gas to Kill Defectors in Vietnam War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The military of the United
States used nerve gas to kill defectors during the
Vietnam war, U.S. media said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Adm. Thomas Moorer, former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff was quoted as saying that sarin nerve gas was used in 1970
in a secret raid into Laos, according to a joint report of Cable
News Networks (CNN) and Time magazine.
</P>
<P>
Other military officials who participated in the operation said
their job was to kill defectors from the U.S. troops. Robert
Buskirk, a platoon leader in the operation, was quoted as
saying: "It wasn't about bringing them back. It was to kill them."
</P>
<P>
Some of the military officials were quoted as saying that the
sarin gas was dropped on more than 20 missions in Laos and then
North Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Moorer said the national security team of President Richard
Nixon approved the use of the nerve gas and the CIA was also
partially responsible for the operation. He was now speaking out
for "his respect for history."
</P>
<P>
The report, a result of a eight-month investigation with 200
people interviewed, was published in the latest edition of the
Time magazine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
