<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Archaelologists Are Not Looking for Genghis Khan's Grave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Cultural affairs officials in
China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region say that archaeologists
have no plans to look for the secret burial place of Genghis Khan,
ancient Mongol ruler.
</P>
<P>
There have been rumors that China would use state-of-the-art
technology like photography from space to look for the grave of
the Mongolian strategist and founder of the Mongol regime in the
early 13th century.
</P>
<P>
According to Su Jun, section chief of the region's culture
department, they have never been told to do this by the central
culture department, and that their primary task is to protect and
rescue cultural relics and historic sites rather than get involved
in archaeological digs, which usually take place at major
infrastructure construction sites.
</P>
<P>
The director of the Genghis Khan Mausoleum Research Institute,
Sareldai, says that excavating the grave of Genghis Khan would be
an act of disrespect for Mongolian customs or tradition, and that
what should be sought is Genghis Khan's enterprising spirit and
his courage, not his remains or buried treasures.
</P>
<P>
Historical reports say that Genghis Khan, once conqueror of
much of the Eurasia, died of illness in 1227 in Liupanshan, in
today's Gansu Province, and was buried in secret by his generals
according to Mongol tradition. Mongol studies specialists around
the world have never agreed on where he had been buried. Some says
it might be in Mongolia, others say it should have been in China,
in his mausoleum in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
Yang Dorj, a Mongolian scholar, says that the myth that Genghis
Khan and his successors -- the Yuan Dynasty emperors -- would have
no graves left behind is an old one. Yong said he believes it is
deeply rooted in the burial customs of Mongols.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
