<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Western Chinese Battle Desert Invasion (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The Taklimakan Desert continues to
move towards the Kunlun Mountains in the southern part of China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region,, after engulfing several cities
on the old Silk Road, but in recent years, it's met with strong
resistance from farmers in the oasis city of Hotan.
</P>
<P>
People there still have to shake the dust off their clothes
before entering silk workshops, but they displayed unique wisdom
and courage in their fight against poverty and desertification,
according to Trine M. Lund-Jensen, assistant representative of the
United Nations Development Program (UNDP), who visited Hotan
recently, and said that it is likely the diligent people can get
rid of poverty in two to three years.
</P>
<P>
The Hotan oasis has a mere tenth of a hectare per capita of
arable land and is one of China's poorest areas. The situation got
worse in the 20 years up to 1995 when 20,000 hectares of oasis was
swallowed up by desert.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, the people of Hotan have never given up in their
struggle against nature, and in recent years, have built water
conservation facilities, developed three-dimentional agriculture,
and turned deserts into orchards in an effort to change this
impoverished land.
</P>
<P>
The snow of the Kunlun Mountains feeds the rivers that run
through the desolate desert, where a group of a thousand bare-foot
farmers are working to stop seepage in the Happiness Canal,
carefully cementing up the cracks.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, in the past several decades,
Hotan's farmers have devoted about a third of their labor to water
conservation projects, and the 36-kilometer Happiness Canal has a
26-kilometer section in the desert. Before the seepage controls,
about fifty pairs of hands were needed to stop the leaks during
irrigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
