<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Beats Russia to Win World Title (with quotes) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Russia took a 9-points halftime lead
and lost the gold medal final 71-65 Sunday to the United States
who recaptured the title at the Women's World Basketball
Championship.
</P>
<P>
This was the sixth time for the Americans to win the world
title in the tournament. The team, which placed third at last
championship, took the previous titles in 1953, 1954, 1979, 1986
and 1990.
</P>
<P>
Center Lisa Leslie led four Americans in double-figures with 20
points. She also grabbed 12 rebounds. Elisha Milton hit 13 and
Ruthie Bolton 11 including three 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
The game tied 63-63 on Russian Svetlana Antipova's lay-up with
1:29 remaining. The United States, however, fired a last charge
headed by Bolton's third three-points and Daw Staley got three
free-throws to seal the victory.
</P>
<P>
Russia opened with a 7-2 lead and extended to 16-8 five minutes
into the game.
</P>
<P>
The United States closed the gap with a 6-0 run for 14-16 but
Russia answered with a 13-6 spurt for 29-20 with 6:30 to play in
the first half.
</P>
<P>
Though trailing at halftime 28-37 but the Americans managed to
equal the score 41-41 with a 13-4 run paced by Leslie's six points
with 12 minutes to go.
</P>
<P>
Russia went ahead as Zassoulska scored six points in a row and
Routkovska tossed in two free throws for 49-46 to keep a marginal
edge until Bolton's second three-pointer with 1:45 left.
</P>
<P>
"We decided this final only in the closing stages with two
three-pointers," U.S. coach Nell Fortner said.
</P>
<P>
Nata Zasslulskaia scored 20 points for Russia, who
disqualified for last tournament in Australia, and Irin
Routkovskaja hit 14 with Elena Baranova 13. Both Routkovskaja and
Baranova also pulled down 9 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
"This was a really great final," said the Russian coach Evgueny
Gomelsky. "To keep the Americans at a 28 points distance in the
first half was a great achievement of our defense. My players
obviously got more tired in the second half."
</P>
<P>
However, the Russian girls received another honour after the
final game when Baranova was announced to be elected as the Most
Valuable Player of the world championship for women by journalists
(including Xinhua News Agency of China) from 14 countries covering
the tournaments.
</P>
<P>
Russia squeezed past Australia 82-76 in Saturday's semi-finals
while the United States beat Brazil 93-72.
</P>
<P>
Eearlier Sunday, Australia rallied to edge defending champion
Brazil 72-67.
</P>
<P>
The next women's world basketball championship will be held in
China in 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
