<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Planes Evacuate 351 Foreigner out of Eritrea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Two planes of the Italian air force
flew 351 foreigners, mostly women and children, out of Eritrean
capital Asmara overnight following last Saturday's bombings of the
city by the Ethiopian planes.
</P>
<P>
The evacuation took place during the 13 hours of safe flying
time granted by the Ethiopian government. Two Italian air force
C-130 planes shuttled between Asmara and Eritrea's neighboring
Djibouti, carrying Italians and 114 people of other nationalities
to safety. The Italians are expected to return home on a specially
commissioned Alitalia fight later.
</P>
<P>
Italian Foreign Ministry said that all Italians requested
evacuation had left Asmara by 06:00 a.m. local time Sunday, the end
of an agreed suspension of hostilities between Ethiopia and
Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
Two C-130s are standing by in Djibouti for emergency evacuation
of the remaining 600 or so Italians if situation further
deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian planes bombed Asmara airport last Saturday for the
third times in two days, persuading some foreign residents there
to leave. "We knew about the skirmishes on the border, but we
didn't think it would come to an all-out war," one evacuee
said. But last Saturday's bombing at the airport "left no room for
doubt."
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian bombing last Saturday is said to be a retaliation for
Friday's bombing by Eritrean planes of the northern Ethiopian city
Mekele, which caused dozens of people dead and a hundred injured.
</P>
<P>
Border clashes between Ethiopia and Eritrea have been
escalating for weeks. The two countries are fighting over a 400-
square-kilometer piece of border land near Mekele. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
