<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Hold First National Ocean Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 500 U.S. scientists,
business leaders, environmentalists and federal officials will
gather this week in Monterey, California, for the country's first
National Ocean Conference.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and cabinet
secretaries will attend the Thursday-Friday conference aimed at
identifying ocean problems, from overfishing to toxic pollution,
and seeking new policies to solve them.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. economy and environment are inextricably linked to the
ocean. More than one-half of Americans live within 80 kilometers
of the coastline. By 2010, that number is expected to reach 75
percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, one-third of the country's GDP is produced in the
coastal zone. Nearly 40 percent of new commercial development and
46 percent of new residential development are built near the
coasts. Nearly 85 percent of all tourist revenues come from
coastal states.
</P>
<P>
But the country has no national strategy for protecting and
sustaining its ocean resources.
</P>
<P>
One of the most critical problems is polluted runoff from storm
drains and other sources, which are wrecking aquatic life.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, there have been 19,000 beach closures
nationwide because of sewage spills. And overfishing is also a big
problem. Of 727 major marine species in U.S. coastal waters, the
status of only 38 percent is known. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
