<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers are as follows:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The newspaper frontpages a report about efforts the city of
Zhongshan made in building itself into a clean, beautiful and
modern city over the past dozen years.
</P>
<P>
The city, the hometown of the Chinese revolutionary forerunner
Dr.Sun Yat-sen, won the United Nations award for its contributions
to the sustainable development of human residence and its
management, along with several awards by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
-- A signed article looks into the problems plaguing the
country's current grain marketing system. It reveals that state
grain firms across the country suffered a loss of 19.7 billion
yuan in 1996, 48 billion yuan in 1997 and 27 billion yuan in the
first quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The article calls for prompt actions to stem the losses and
points out reforms as the only way out.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Heilongjiang and Jilin, two provinces in northeast China,
known as the country's bread-basket, have started to reform
state-run grain enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Grain firms in Heilongjiang are trying ways to relieve their
operational difficulties by handling purchase and sales by
themselves while developing grain processing industries. Grain
administrations in Jilin have intensified their efforts to cut
grain stockpiles in the province and expect to reduce losses by 10
percent by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
-- To tap the domestic market and promote housing reform system,
financial institutions in capital city Beijing have issued various
mortgage loans to encourage residents to buy their own homes.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Alarmed by a succession of natural disasters since the
beginning of the year, the Ministry of Civil Affairs has
reinforced its efforts to reduce their impact by improving the
collection of information and allocating more funds in the wake of
the disasters.
</P>
<P>
-- An increasing number of Chinese adolescents are plagued by
eye problems arising from an excessively heavy study load and lack
of eye care.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health had designated June 6 as National Eye
Care Day in a bid to raise public awareness of the need to protect
eyes.
</P>
<P>
-- Beijing Municipal People's Congress approved rules over the
weekend to protect ancient trees.
</P>
<P>
-- Fourteen people, including managers and a Hong Kong boss,
have been arrested for torturing workers in Shenzhen Special
Economic Zone in south China's Guangdong Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
