<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Economy on Threshold of Depression, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- An economic guru said Indonesia's
economy is on the threshold of a depression and suggested that
small and medium-scale businesses be reinvigorated, reported The
Jakarta Post Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Reinvigorating these businesses is most urgent and imperative
now to rescue our economy," said Sumitro Djojohadikusumo here over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Small and medium-scale businesses were the back-bone of the
country's economy in terms of productive employment, real income
and foreign exchange generation.
</P>
<P>
He said the government should lobby strongly the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) to immediately allocate between 3 billion and
5 billion U.S. dollars out of its sponsored 43-billion-U.S.-dollar
bailout fund into a trust fund to extend credits at concessional
interest rates to small and medium-size businesses.
</P>
<P>
If the IMF does not agree on such an allocation, he said, the
government should allocate that fund from its international
reserve.
</P>
<P>
Last January, Sumitro warned that the nation could plunge into
a prolonged depression if economic and political reforms were not
implemented speedily, firmly and consistently.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's Central Bureau of Statistics recently predicted a
total negative gross domestic product growth of over 10 percent
for this year and inflation exceeding 85 percent.
</P>
<P>
"My own prediction is a contraction of between 10 and 15
percent and inflation minimally at 100 percent," Sumitro said.
</P>
<P>
The 81-year-old guru was a minister in the late 1960s and
1970s. He said he had actually decided to retire from economic
policy debates unless an emergency situation arose.
</P>
<P>
"The present crisis is a call of duty for me to speak my mind,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President B.J. Habibie told reporters over the
weekend that Indonesia would stick to an IMF reform program.
</P>
<P>
"We have a program with the IMF and we are going to follow that
program and make the best out of that," he said.
</P>
<P>
The head of the Asia-pacific department of IMF Hubert Neiss
will head a team to review progress in reforms and assess new data
and revise figures and assumptions about Indonesia's economy. The
team is expected in Jakarta on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Habibie stressed that the exchange rate between the rupiah and
the U.S. dollar was important, but that stability and control of
inflation were more important.
</P>
<P>
"If it (the rupiah) is stable and inflation is under control,
we can adjust," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980608.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
