<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, June 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat visited Sudan
Sunday in his continued bid to push for holding an Arab summit to
pressure Israel to carry out the long-delayed further redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Arafat concluded his several-hour visit following talks with
President Omar al-Bashir on the Middle East peace process and
bilateral ties. (Sudan-Palestine-Arafat Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait on Sunday flatly rejected the Iraqi
statement that shed doubt on U.N. Security Council Resolution 833
on the demarcation of the Kuwait-Iraq borders.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan was reported to have
said in Rabat, Morocco, that there was no legal value in the
Resolution 833 concerning the demarcation of the borders between
Kuwait and Iraq. (Kuwait-Iraq-Demarcation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair discussed the
crisis in Kosovo in phone calls to U.S. President Bill Clinton and
Russian President Boris Yeltsin, BBC TV reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Blair agreed with Clinton to send a strong message criticizing
the acts of Yugoslav forces in the province, it added.
</P>
<P>
While talking with Yeltsin, the premier urged him to help
persuade Belgrade to stop "barbarism" against Albanian civilians
in Kosovo, BBC TV said. (UK-Blair-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- India Sunday evening rejected the U.N. Security
Council resolution issued Saturday urging India and Pakistan to
halt their further nuclear weapons program.
</P>
<P>
India's senior External Affairs Ministry officials regarded the
 resolution as "ultra virus" and "unacceptable". Following up New
Delhi's strong reaction to the resolution, the officials said that
exception had been taken to the "deeply offensive" tone and the
manner in which it had addressed India. (India-UN Resolution)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel Sunday called on
NATO to speed up its consideration of sending troops to Albania
and the Republic of Macedonia in order to prevent the escalating
Kosovo conflict from spilling over to the neighboring region.
</P>
<P>
"Macedonia and Albania must be stabilized. The political
pressure on Belgrade must also be shored up militarily," said
Kinkel in a statement issued in Bonn Sunday. (Germany-NATO-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- Sudanese President Omar al-Bashir renewed Sunday
his country's support for holding a summit grouping all the Arab
countries to discuss problems facing the Arab nation, including
the Mideast peace.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with visiting Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat here, al-Bashir told reporters that
the Arab nation is in need of reviewing the situation in the Arab
arena to adopt a position that guarantees the restoration of the
Arab rights, safety and security. (Sudan-Arafat-Arab Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran on Sunday expressed serious concern over recent
military clashes between Ethiopia and Eritrea, calling on the two
African countries to solve their disputes through political means.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi said that
it is incorrect to solve differences and disputes by resorting to
force and hostility, Tehran radio reported.
(Iran-Ethiopia-Eritrea) 
</P>
