<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Law Enforcement Officers Increase in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Full-time state and local law
enforcement officers increased by more than 19 percent between
1992 and 1996, with a larger percentage of uniformed officers
patroling that nation's streets, the Justice Department said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A Bureau of Justice Statistics report said the number of law
enforcement officers grew during the four-year period by more than
68,000 to reach 423,000.
</P>
<P>
Of those officers, 64 percent were uniformed personnel whose
regular duties included responding to calls for service, compared
with 59 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Proponents of community policing applauded the increase as
evidence that a crime bill to put more police on the streets and
in partnership with neighborhoods is working.
</P>
<P>
"Not only has there been a huge increase in the number of men
and women working in law enforcement, but local agencies are
committing a larger percentage of sworn officers to patrol
functions and community policing activities," said Joseph E.
Brann, director of the Office of Community Oriented Policing
Services (COPS). The COPS program has funded more than 75,000
additional officers and deputies since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Representative Charles E. Schumer, a Democrat who sponsored the
crime bill which produced the COPS program, linked increases in
police officers on the streets with decreases in recorded violent
crimes.
</P>
<P>
In November, the Bureau of Justice Statistics reported that
violent crimes against Americans had fallen 10 percent in 1996
from the previous year, hitting the lowest level since the survey
began 23 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
The report also found that the total number of full-time state
and local officers with arrest powers increased by 59,000 since
1992 to total 663,535 in 1996. Of the full-time sworn officers, 15
percent were assigned to investigative duties.
</P>
<P>
New York City's Police Department, the largest law enforcement
agency in the country, employed 36,813 full-time officers in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
